<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Illegal Gold Panners Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 7 (xinhua) -- More than 200,000 Zimbabweans are
believed to be surviving solely on illegal gold panning, the
Zimbabwean News Agency Ziana reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
President of the National Minerals Association of Zimbabwe
Giles Munyoro Saturday told Ziana that Zimbabwe could be losing
millions of Dollars through illegal gold panning as some
companies are taking advantage of the ignorance of panners from
whom they buy the gold at low prices.
</P>
<P>
Munyoro said his association had also noticed that most of the
miners who had licenses were foreigners at the expense of locals,
raising fears that some of the gold was being smuggled out of the
country.
</P>
<P>
He said it was also disturbing that some individuals in
leadership positions in the rural areas were ignoring the
environmental damage arising from gold panning because they were
benefiting from the illegal activities.
</P>
<P>
He said, ''the government should intervene and severely punish
those culprits.''
</P>
<P>
Some private companies recently called on small scale miners
and other gold dealers to sell their gold to them to avoid
problems faced when they sell it to a few selected and licensed
dealers.
</P>
<P>
However, it is feared that this could encourage intensive gold
panning and criminal activities because no license would be
required to sell the gold.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe is the third largest gold producer in Africa after
South Africa and Ghana. 
</P>
</TEXT>
