<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Banks' Profit Growth Slows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 7 (Xinhua) -- Canadian banks' profit growth has
slowed from last year though they turned in another solid quarter
of earnings in the period ended on January 31, reports said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In total, Canada's six biggest commercial banks reported 1.89
billion dollars (1.3 billion USD) in profit in the first quarter
of 1998, up eight percent from a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
But that was down nearly 10 percent from 2.06 billion dollars
in the fourth quarter of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Of all six banks, the National Bank of Canada posted the
highest earnings growth of 20 percent year-over-year, followed by
Royal Bank of Canada at 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Montreal ranked third with an earnings growth rate
of 12 percent, while both Toronto Dominion Bank and Bank of Nova
Scotia fourth with growth rates of 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
The one disappointment was Canadian Imperial Bank of Commerce,
where earnings fell eight percent because of trading losses in
Asia and acquisition costs.
</P>
<P>
The country's Big Six banks are expected to have good, if
unspectacular, earnings growth over the rest of the year for the
industry, the reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
