<HEADLINE> Nujoma on Namibia's Official Language </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 7 (Xinhua) -- Namibian President Sam
Nujoma said in Windhoek Saturday that his country is a
multi-racial and multi-cultural society, and the German language
cannot be given special status above others.
</P>
<P>
Nujoma said Namibia become independent in 1990 and chose
English as the official language in order to establish means of
communication which would unite the people and not divide them.
</P>
<P>
The president was responding to a call by visiting German
President Roman Herzog to make German an official medium of
institution in Namibian schools, the Southern African
Broadcasting Association reported.
</P>
<P>
Nujoma said choosing German as an official medium of
institution for schools may cause division within society.
</P>
<P>
When English was chosen as the official language, the
intention was not to diminish the importance of other Namibian
languages, said Nujoma.
</P>
<P>
Herzog is on a seven-day state visit to Namibia.
</P>
<P>
Germany colonized Namibia following the partitioning of Africa
at the infamous Berlin Conference of 1884. 
</P>
</TEXT>
