<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Farmers Commend Land Reform Measures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 7 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean farmers have welcomed
the government's decision to delist farms belonging to indigenous
farmers from over 1,400 farms it has designated to compulsorily
acquire for resettlement of thousands of landless blacks.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Director of the Zimbabwe Farmers Union (ZFU) Emmerson
Zhou Saturday told the Zimbabwe News Agency Ziana that the
government had shown its willingness to engage in constructive
dialog with interested parties for an amicable conclusion on the
controversial land issue.
</P>
<P>
"In entertaining alternative land offers the government must
ensure that such land offers adequate opportunities to new
settlers," Zhou said.
</P>
<P>
The government recently announced that it was to delist five
categories of farms from the 1,471 compulsorily acquired for
resettlement.
</P>
<P>
These categories included farms offered to the government for
resettlement purposes, farms owned by indigenous persons,
plantation farms, those with Zimbabwe Investment Center permits
and farms belonging to missionaries and church organizations.
</P>
<P>
One of the objectives of the land reform program was to
indigenize the large-scale commercial farming sector and to date
only 10 percent of the country's commercial farms belong to
indigenous farmers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
