<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Students to Demonstrate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 7 (Xinhua) -- The National Executive Council of
the Zimbabwe National Students Union (ZINASU) Saturday resolved
that students will go on a nationwide demonstration Monday to
press the government to review their pay-outs.
</P>
<P>
ZINASU Vice President Fortune Mguni said after meeting with 38
presidents representing tertiary institutions here Saturday, the
only way forward after the government's negative response to
their requests was for students in all regions to go on peaceful
demonstrations, the Zimbabwe News Agency Ziana reported.
</P>
<P>
"After the demonstrations on Monday, we urge all students to
resume classes, and from Tuesday we will give the government at
most three weeks (up to March 27) to respond to our legitimate
request for increments," Mguni said.
</P>
<P>
In the event of the government failing to respond favorably to
their demands, the ZINASU National Executive Council would meet
again to chart the way forward.
</P>
<P>
Last week, students went on a week-long nationwide class
boycott pressing for a 253 percent pay-out increment for tertiary
students and about 40 percent for university students. 
</P>
</TEXT>
