<HEADLINE> Canadian Gasoline Dirtiest Among Major Economies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 7 (Xinhua) -- Canadian gasoline has the highest
average level of smog-causing sulphur among major developed
economies, a report said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
High-sulphur gasoline reduces the efficiency of catalytic
converters and degrades the performance of oxygen sensors, both
devices used to make car exhaust cleaner.
</P>
<P>
In Canada, the dirtiest gasoline, as far as sulphur was
concerned, was found in the country's most populous province of
Ontario, which relies on aging oil refineries that use a large
amount of high-sulphur crude as a raw material.
</P>
<P>
Ontario gasoline has about 17 times the average sulphur content
allowed in California. It also exceeds average levels in Europe
and Japan by substantial margins, according to the Globe and Mail
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
While international sulphur levels have been declining in
recent years, the amount of this pollutant in Ontario gasolines
has been increasing.
</P>
<P>
"Ontario levels are the highest I've ever seen in the developed
countries," a senior engineer at Environment Canada was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The findings were part of the most extensive studies to date on
the sulphur content of Canada gasolines, the likely health effects
of the pollutant and the costs and benefits of reducing levels.
</P>
<P>
The studies was designed to help federal, provincial and
territorial governments draft new national standards for gasoline
composition, the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
