<HEADLINE> UNITA Claims Total Implementation of Peace Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 7 (Xinhua) -- The National Union for Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA) Saturday said it has complied with
the Angolan peace pact of 1994 by demobilizing its 70,000 troops.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan former rebel movement said in a statement issued
here that about 6,000 of the 8,000 troops who were still armed in
December have laid down their arms.
</P>
<P>
The statement came as diplomats overseeing Angola's peace
process are stepping up efforts to salvage the accord after
another deadline in late February passed without its full
implementation.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations mediator, Behrrooz Sandry, has held
closed-door talks in Luanda after UNITA failed to meet its
deadline on Thursday to declare it had fully demobilized its
troops.
</P>
<P>
Demobilization of UNITA soldiers was laid down in the 1994
Lusaka peace accord which ended the nearly 20 years of civil war
of the country.
</P>
<P>
However, the government complained that UNITA had not
demobilized its soldiers, given up its territory to the
government and renounced its private radio as laid down by the
Lusaka pact.
</P>
<P>
In the statement, the opposition movement has assured the
Angolan government and the United Nations that its remaining
troops will complete handing in their weapons by the 15th of this
month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
