<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Minister: UN Inspections to Prove No Banned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 7 (Xinhua) -- Iraq said Saturday that the
upcoming U.N. inspections of its presidential sites will prove
that it has no weapons of mass destruction and lead to the lifting
of U.N. economic sanctions on it.
</P>
<P>
"It is just impossible" for Iraq to hide biological, chemical
weapons and components or factories producing the weapons in its
presidential palaces, Iraqi Oil Minister Amir Mohammed Rashid told
Xinhua in an exclusive interview.
</P>
<P>
"Now we have agreed to open these sites to (arms inspectors and
diplomats) to make sure that they will realize what the Americans
have said is a big lie," Rashid said.
</P>
<P>
Iraq reached an agreement with the United Nations on February
23 to grant free and unconditional access to eight presidential
sites to a special team comprising U.N. arms inspectors in Iraq
and senior diplomats appointed by the U.N. chief Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
The arms inspectors must certify that Iraq has destroyed all
its weapons of mass destruction before the U.N. Security Council
lifts the crippling economic sanctions imposed on Iraq in 1990
after its invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Rashid said the allegations made by the United States that Iraq
has weapons of mass destruction in presidential palaces are
pretexts for military aggression and continued sanctions against
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
In the summer of 1996, Rolf Ekeus, the then chairman of the
U.N. Special Commission, or UNSCOM, said that Iraq was hiding five
to 15 missiles and two missile launchers, and he and American
officials made a lot of fuss about it, he said.
</P>
<P>
But excavation of destroyed missile parts proved that Ekeus'
allegations were baseless, said the minister, who is one of Iraq's
top negotiators dealing with the U.N. arms inspections.
</P>
<P>
"Now they are accusing Iraq of hiding biological and chemical
weapons inside presidential sites," Rashid said.
</P>
<P>
The sites are now open to the arms inspectors, who will find
nothing, he added.
</P>
<P>
Iraq will have no problem with the U.N. inspectors, if they
behave as technical experts, Rashid said.
</P>
<P>
But he warned of "problems" if the inspectors are influenced by
the "political agenda and objectives" of Washington.
</P>
<P>
The United States would try to make problems through its agents
in the UNSCOM, Rashid said, expressing hope that with the active
participation of friendly countries, problems will become less.
</P>
<P>
"We are not saying it will become zero, it will become less, it
will be difficult for the Americans to make a crisis again," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Rashid said he hopes the inspection of presidential sites will
be completed within weeks or months, because there are only eight
of them.
</P>
<P>
"We think one of the biggest advantages of the crisis (we have
got) is now all the world is looking at Iraq," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
It "will see what the inspectors are doing," he added
</P>
<P>
U.N. arms inspectors have visited thousands of sites in Iraq,
but they have failed to discover any single weapon of mass
destruction or its components, or any prohibited material, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Sanctions should have been lifted long time ago," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
"We are hopeful, we are optimistic and we hope that with the
support of friendly countries and the intervention of the U.N.
secretary-general, the sanctions will be lifted very soon,"
Rashid said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
