<HEADLINE> Iraq Urges World Media to Focus on Inspection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 7 (Xinhua) -- Iraq on Saturday urged world
media to focus their attention on results of upcoming inspections
of Iraqi presidential sites by U.N. arms inspectors.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with Xinhua, Iraqi Oil Minister Amir
Mohammed Rashid said the world media should focus on what the
inspectors will find, and not be diverted by new allegations
against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Rashid said Iraq is confident that U.N. inspectors will not
find a single piece of weapon of mass destruction or its
components in Iraqi presidential sites, because Iraq has destroyed
all those weapons and has nothing to hide.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. inspection of the presidential sites, Rashid said,
will prove to the world the allegation that Iraq hides banned
weapons in those sites is "a big lie."
</P>
<P>
He said in the summer of 1996, Rolf Ekeus, the then chairman of
the U.N. Special Committee (UNSCOM) in charge of weapons
inspection in Iraq, told the world that Iraq was hiding five to 15
missiles and two launchers.
</P>
<P>
After months of excavation of destroyed missile parts, Rashid
said, the Iraqi side proved to Ekeus with full documentation that
every piece of the missiles and launchers has been destroyed.
</P>
<P>
However, neither a U.S. official nor a leader of UNSCOM talked
about it, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Now they are accusing Iraq of hiding biological and chemical
weapons inside presidential sites," the minister said. "The sites
are open now, they will visit them. When they finish it, they
might create another problem so that you do not remember the
original one."
</P>
<P>
Rashid said the world media should not let their focus be
diverted again by possible new allegations against Iraq. The
public opinion should be aware of the fact that the United States
is looking for a new allegation to justify the continuation of
sanctions on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. sanctions were imposed in 1990 after Iraq invaded
Kuwait. They cannot be lifted unless the UNSCOM verifies that Iraq
is free of weapons of mass destruction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
