<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Calls for World's Proper Assessment on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 7 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Ministry Saturday
in a press release expressed hope that the Russian-speaker's
protest incident in Riga on March 3 will be "properly assessed in
the world."
</P>
<P>
The Interfax news agency reported that the ministry hoped that
the world community would make a collective effort to improve the
human rights situation in Latvia as soon as possible and "put an
end to the policy of insults and humiliation in relation to a
large group of the country's permanent residents."
</P>
<P>
The dramatic events in Riga provide one more proof of the
extremely serious situation in Latvia already known to the world,
the document said.
</P>
<P>
"The Latvian authorities' cynicism is limitless. Prime Minister
Guntars Krasts has even gone so far as to accuse Russia of
organizing the disturbances in Riga," the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
It criticized the Latvian authorities for violation of
political, civil, social, economic and cultural rights of hundreds
of thousands of residents who do not have the status of the
so-called 'title nation'.
</P>
<P>
The Russian Foreign Ministry stated that it has drawn the
attention of the U.N., the Council of Europe and the Organization
for Security and Cooperation in Europe to these ultrages.
</P>
<P>
On the same day Latvian Prime Minister Guntars Krasts also
stated that "no violations of human rights" took place during the
picket outside the Riga city legislature on March 3.
</P>
<P>
He said following a Cabinet session that "the Latvian police
acted properly and there were no instances of human rights
violations."
</P>
<P>
About 2,000 ethnic Russians last Tuesday held a picket in front
of the building of the city legislature in Riga in protest against
rising tariffs. The Latvian police used force against them,
thereby eliciting a strong negative response in Moscow, which
considered the incident as an instance of gross violation of the
ethnic Russian's rights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
