<HEADLINE> Israeli-Palestinian Peace Process Moving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 7 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) President Yasser Arafat said Saturday that the
Israeli-Palestinian peace process is moving backward and the
situation is very dangerous.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a meeting of Palestinian Council in Gaza Strip,
Arafat warned that the peace process, which has been stalled for a
year over next Israeli troop pullback in the West Bank, is "about
to breathe its last breath."
</P>
<P>
According to a report of Israel Radio, Arafat again blamed
Israel for the breakdown in the peace talks, charging that the
Israeli government is willing to see "the peace process become
part of the past."
</P>
<P>
Arafat also hinted at reforms in his authority, saying that
"while all of us make mistakes," the PNA is merely experiencing
the growing pains of any new democratic government. He noted that
he is open to some change and reorganization in the authority.
</P>
<P>
The PNA has been suffering from mismanagement and
corruption. The Council members were seriously critical of it and
even threatened a no-confidence notion at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
Before Arafat began his speech, the council had reelected Abu
Ala as its speaker for a third one-year term. Abu Ala defeated two
challengers in the election, wining 55 of 70 votes cast by the
88-member council.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the report said that more than 2,000 Palestinians
rallied in the West Bank city of Hebron Saturday to mark the
massacre of 29 Muslim worshippers at a Hebron mosque by a Jewish
gunman four years ago.
</P>
<P>
Protesters carried coffins, which were inscribed with words
"peace process," "security council resolution," and "Israeli
justice." 
</P>
