<HEADLINE> Diplomats, Refugees Trickle Back to Freetown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 7 (Xinhua) -- Diplomats and refugees are
trickling back to the Sierra Leonean capital Freetown, ahead of
the return of ousted President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A report reaching here said Saturday that British High
Commissioner Peter Penfold and European Community Representative
Emilio Perez Porras returned to Freetown Friday night with
Kabbah's Foreign Minister Shirley Gbujama.
</P>
<P>
The two were the first foreign diplomats to return since the
west African peace-keeping force known as ECOMOG drove the
military junta led by Major Johnny Koroma from the capital in
mid-February.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, officials at the Freetown Port said a boat brought
home 700 refugees from neighboring Guinea early Saturday and was
due to leave to repatriate more. Relief officials estimated that
there are about 300,000 Sierra Leonean refugees in Guinea.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG has captured most major towns in Sierra Leone, although
troops loyal to Koroma remained active in the south and east.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG sources said they are planning to deploy forces heavily
in Freetown to protect Kabbah, who has been in Guinea since
ousted by Koroma's coup last May. 
</P>
