<HEADLINE> Egyptian President Calls for "Responsible" Press </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 7 (Xinhua) -- After several run-ins with domestic
newspapers, the Egyptian government Saturday called for a
responsible press that places national interests as a high
priority.
</P>
<P>
President Hosni Mubarak outlined the guidelines for being a
"responsible press" at his meeting Saturday with the newly-elected
Higher Press Council, which groups the country's top media
administrators.
</P>
<P>
"Journalists are guided only by their conscience and the law,"
the president was quoted by Council Chairman Mustafa Kamal Helmi
as telling reporters.
</P>
<P>
"So respect of law, constitution, social values, traditions and
the supreme national interests should be the key tenets needed to
enable pressmen to proceed in their sublime message," he said.
</P>
<P>
Addressing reporters, Helmi also lashed out at the writings
"harming values, traditions and higher interests of the Egyptian
society."
</P>
<P>
"Veteran journalists, either at national or party newspapers,
have denounced writings made by intruders to the press community,"
he said after the meeting, which was attended by Prime Minister
Kamal el-Ganzouri, Information Minister Safwat al-Sherif and Head
of the Presidential Cabinet Zakaria Azmi.
</P>
<P>
The Higher Press Council will provide the atmosphere favorable
for responsible press heeding values and principles of the society
and stand against any violation of these principles, said Helmi,
also speaker of the Shura Council.
</P>
<P>
Three journalists of the Misr al-Fataa weekly newspaper were
charged Wednesday with libeling Egypt's finance minister in
articles that accused him of corruption. If convicted, the three
men can face up to three years in prison.
</P>
<P>
On February 26, the government banned publication of the
independent weekly Al Destour three days after it printed a faxed
statement from Gamaa Al Islamiya, Egypt's main militant group.
</P>
<P>
A Cairo court on February 24 sentenced two reporters at the
Islamist Al-Shaab newspaper to one year in jail with labor and
fines for libeling former Interior Minister Hassan Al Alfi and his
sons.
</P>
<P>
Opposition and independent editors have criticized these
developments as blows to the freedom of press in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian laws allow only the government, political parties and
government-approved companies to publish newspapers here. Other
off-shore publications have to obtain a three-month renewable
permit from the Ministry of Information to go to print in Egypt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
