<DOCNO> XIE19980308.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Zambian Govt, Labor Dispute Remains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 7 (Xinhua) -- There is no signal that the Zambia
Congress of Trade Union (ZCTU) will call off the nation-wide
strike planned for Monday to protest a government plan to freeze
the wage of public service workers for this year.
</P>
<P>
To avoid the work stoppage, President Frederick Chiluba
promised Friday not to de-register the trade unions even if they
organize the strike.
</P>
<P>
He also said that trade unions have the right to go on strike
but the situation should be justified, adding that there is no
valid ground for a strike on March 9 because what good labor
leaders should do is to plan other tactics to resolve the impasse
between their members and the government.
</P>
<P>
The president further said the freeze on wage increments is
restricted only to public service workers while others in the
private sector are free to negotiate better conditions of service
with their respective employers as they are not affected by the
government plan.
</P>
<P>
He asked government ministers not to intimidate workers but
convince them about the importance of the government decisions
like the freeze on wage increments.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba argued that the wage freeze is meant to enable the
government to down-size the bloated civil service which has
become unmanageable.
</P>
<P>
But he stopped short of meeting workers' demand.
</P>
<P>
Although ZCTU welcomed Chiluba's statement as positive, it
maintained that the strike will still go ahead as planned because
their demand for rescinding the wage freeze has not been met.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, Labor Minister Newstea Zimba said that the
government will not yield to demands for discussions under
duress.
</P>
<P>
Zimba said the government is willing to have dialog with the
unions but will not do so until the Zambia Congress of Trade
Unions (ZCTU) withdraws its threats to strike.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Zambia Federation of Employers (ZFE) told its
members Friday to discipline workers who will show solidarity
with the public service workers.
</P>
<P>
ZFE President Francis Simenda has appealed to ZCTU to avoid
the work stoppage, saying that the Tripartite Consultative Labor
Council meeting scheduled for later this month should be used as
a forum to discuss all grievances the labor movement may have.
</P>
<P>
"Dialog is the only way in issues of industrial relations if
we have to resolve our problems. Threats and confrontations
should be avoided," he said.
</P>
<P>
Last Sunday, Labor Minister Zimba warned the public service
workers of instant dismissal if they take part in the strike. He
also warned that unions organizing the strike risk being
de-registered.
</P>
<P>
However, ZCTU General Secretary Alec Chirwa said early this
week that "it is unthinkable to impose a wage freeze on workers
in a liberalized economy."
</P>
<P>
"The government is imposing a wage freeze on workers who are
earning far below a living wage," he noted, adding, "this is the
most inhuman treatment the government can inflict on workers."
</P>
<P>
Chirwa lamented that the cost of living is already beyond the
reach of the majority of Zambians and the government is adding
salt to injury by taking away the little the workers in the
public service are getting.
</P>
<P>
Some opposition parties have expressed their solidarity with
the public service workers. The Party for Morality and Economic
Progress said the wage freeze is not synonymous with the
government policy of a liberalized economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
