<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 7 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's Deputy Minister
of Energy and Minerals Manju Msambya will leave Sunday for London
to attend a conference on mining in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Msambya told reporters Saturday that the conference aims to
provide British companies with business opportunities in the fast
growing mining sector in tropical Africa, especially in Tanzania,
Ghana and Zambia.
</P>
<P>
He said the conference, organized by Britain's Department of
Trade and Industry, will be a chance for Tanzania to attract
investments.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania's output of mineral exploration surpassed 80 million
U.S. Dollars in 1997, making the country the fourth largest in
sub-Sahara Africa in mining terms, after South Africa, Ghana and
Zimbabwe, statistics indicated.
</P>
<P>
The government has provided legislation and tax and fiscal
incentives to attract further mining investment, Minister of
Energy and Minerals Abdallah Kigoda told reporters last week.
</P>
<P>
With the new mineral policy in 1997 already implemented and
the new Mining Act tabled in parliament awaiting approval, the
investment in Tanzania's mining sector is expected to triple by
the turn of the century, Kigoda said.
</P>
<P>
The deputy minister, to be accompanied by a senior geologist
at the ministry, Godwin Nyello, will take part in a two-day
program of visits and meetings next week in Britain. 
</P>
