<HEADLINE> Iraq: Anglo-Saxons Still Dominate Inspection Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 7 (Xinhua)-- Iraqi Oil Minister Amir Mohammed
Rashid said Saturday the U.N. arms inspection team headed by
American Scott Ritter is still dominated by Anglo-Saxons.
</P>
<P>
Rashid told Xinhua that the 50-member arms inspection team,
which arrived here Thursday, includes 12 Americans, six Britons,
and 10 Australians.
</P>
<P>
"Anglo-Saxons are the dominant core of that team and they
account for more than half of the team's 50 inspectors," said the
minister.
</P>
<P>
In mid-January, a 16-member weapons inspection team headed by
Ritter was barred by Iraq from carrying out any activities in Iraq
on grounds that its composition is imbalanced. That team included
nine Americans and five Britons.
</P>
<P>
But the minister noted that Ritter's team has nothing to do
with Iraqi presidential sites, which had been the core of a crisis
defused late last month. "He (Ritter) is inspecting sensitive
security sites," he said.
</P>
<P>
The crisis was triggered when Iraq refused entry of
presidential sites to U.N. weapons inspectors, citing national
sovereignty. The U.S. and Britain threatened military action
before the U.N. chief Kofi Annan signed an accord with Baghdad on
February 23 to allow a team of inspectors and diplomats free
inspection of the sites. 
</P>
