<DOCNO> XIE19980308.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African C. Bank Introduces Repo Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 7 (Xinhua) -- Governor of South African
Reserve Bank Chris Stals Saturday announced the introduction of
the new repurchase rate for banks, South African Press
Association (SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
SAPA quoted Stals as saying that the repo rate would be fixed
at 15 percent from March 9 to 13. This will reduce the effective
cost of borrowing from the Reserve Bank by one percentage point.
</P>
<P>
From March 16, 1998, the bank will only announce a maximum
amount for the daily tender of repos, and the average rate will
be determined through the tender mechanism.
</P>
<P>
Stals said the marginal lending rate would be fixed at 16
percent, which is at the level of the old bank rate, for at least
two weeks as from March 9.
</P>
<P>
He said in changing the monetary policy framework, the Reserve
Bank, the country's central bank, had given recognition to the
relatively high level of real interest rates in South Africa by
fixing the first repo rate one full percentage point below the
current bank rate.
</P>
<P>
This is, however, not necessarily part of a continuing process
of a relaxation of monetary policy measures. The high rates of
growth in money supply and bank credit extension, the Southeast
Asian crisis and recent developments in the current account of
the balance of payments, caution against a premature excessive
relaxation in the existing restrictive monetary policy measure.
</P>
<P>
He also announced that a new averaging provision would be
introduced in the application of the minimum cash reserves which
banks had to maintain at the Reserve Bank from March 20.
</P>
<P>
To simplify the current cash reserve requirements, the Reserve
Bank has decided to apply only one reserve ratio of 2.5 percent
on the total liabilities of banks, beginning from the maintenance
period starting April 23, 1998. This will slightly reduce the
amount of the minimum cash reserves, but no interest will be paid
on any part of the minimum cash reserve balances.
</P>
<P>
Reserve Bank debentures for the management of bank liquidity
would also be issued from time to time. The issue of these
debentures will partially compensate banks for the loss of
interest that they currently earn on part of their cash reserves,
and will establish a role for Reserve Bank debentures in the new
system of accommodation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
