<HEADLINE> Turkish Urges Belgrade to Solve Kosovo Unrest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 7 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail
Cem said on Saturday that the present violence in Kosovo must be
dealt with in a proper manner, the Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference in the central Turkish city of
Kayseri, Cem said that Turkey, as a power in the region, is
extremely sensitive over the tensions in the southern Yugoslav
province.
</P>
<P>
Recalling the Balkan region as a historical hotbed of war, Cem
warned that the Kosovo unrest might spread to other Balkan
nations and will damage stability of the region.
</P>
<P>
He said Turkey wants a peaceful solution to the crisis in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"Of course we respect Yugoslavia's sovereignty and territorial
integrity, but Turkey cannot remain indifferent to oppression,
torture and killing of people," he said.
</P>
<P>
When asked whether he will present a proposal to Yugoslavian
President Slobodan Milosevic during his trip to Belgrade, Cem said
that this is not the aim of this visit.
</P>
<P>
He said: "We will convey our own concerns and ideas."
</P>
<P>
Pointed out that Ankara has been closely following
developments in Kosovo, the Turkish foreign minister said that
Turkey hope calmness could be restored soon in the region.
</P>
<P>
He said that he will meet his Yugoslavian counterpart in
Belgrade and then convey to Milosevic a letter from Turkish
President Suleyman Demirel concerning the Kosovo clashes.
</P>
<P>
Cem is scheduled to fly to the Yugoslavian capital on Saturday
evening, according to an early official press release.
</P>
<P>
At least 45 Albanians and six Serb police were killed in Kosovo
since an armed conflict between ethnic Albanian separatists and
police broke up on March 1.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz told Milosevic
by telephone that Turkey was concerned about the bloody clashes
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has shared historically close ties with Albania and
ethnic Albanians in the Balkans. 
