<P>
BRUSSELS, March 7 (Xinhua) -- Governments of the 15 European
Union (EU) member states are due to decide on March 18 whether to
approve the marketing throughout the Union of four new varieties
of genetically modified maize and rapeseed, it was learned here
today.
</P>
<P>
The products concerned are maize strains produced by the U.S.
chemicals company Monsanto, Swiss drugs firm Novartis and German
group AgrEvo, and an oilseed rape variety produced by AgrEvo,
sources said here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
All four were approved by an EU scientific advisory panel on
February 12 in a move welcomed by the biotechnology industry.
</P>
<P>
However, the panel's advice is not final and the EU states
will have to endorse it formally before marketing can go ahead.
</P>
<P>
Green Euro-MPs and scientists called on Friday for a moratorium
on all authorizations of genetically modified organisms (GMO)
until solid research data could prove they posed no long-term
danger to health or the environment.
</P>
<P>
Two of the new varieties, the new Monsanto and Novartis maize
strains, have been engineered to resist the European corn borer by
the addition of a gene which causes the plant to produce a protein
that kills the insect.
</P>
<P>
The European Association for Bioindustries said this was a new
and environmentally friendly way to control devastating insect
pests and ensure yield.
</P>
<P>
But environmentalists and the authorities in Austria, Denmark
and Greece have voiced concern that the additional gene could
initially kill benign insects as well as the corn borer and over
time lead to the pest developing a resistance to the toxin.
</P>
<P>
Austria and Luxembourg have imposed domestic bans on another
strain of Novartis GMO-maize carrying the gene, in defiance of an
EU decision in 1996 to authorize it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
