<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish FM Leaves for Belgrade to Discuss Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 7 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail
Cem flew to Belgrade on Saturday evening on a mission to help find
a solution to the violence in Kosovo province of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters at the Ankara Esenboga Airport, Cem said
that it is Turkey's attitude that "the bloodshed in Kosovo must be
stopped."
</P>
<P>
The semi-official Anatolia News Agency quoted Cem as saying
that "We hope that this visit will be an action that can make
contributions to a peaceful solution to the crisis."
</P>
<P>
Cem said that Turkey has conveyed such views of point to the
governments of Albania, Macedonia as well as Bulgaria, adding that
Ankara is worried that the disturbances in Kosovo could spread to
the whole Balkans.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said that he will meet President of the
Yugoslavian Federation Slobodan Milosevic on Sunday morning and
convey him a letter from his Turkish counterpart Suleyman Demirel.
</P>
<P>
Demirel's letter called on the Milosevic government to
exercise the greatest restraint concerning the Kosovo unrest, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
