<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private Car Registrations Rise in CEEC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 7 (Xinhua) -- No fewer than 373,000 private
cars were registered for the first time in nine countries of
Central and Eastern Europe during the first half of 1997, it was
learned here today.
</P>
<P>
The Czech Republic accounted for a third of the total, with
119,800 registrations during the first half of 1997 and 62,900
during the third quarter, European Report, a twice-weekly
newsletter published here Saturday, quoted Eurostat as saying.
</P>
<P>
Lithuania was in second place with 94,200, after placing first
in 1996 with 186,900. Romania took the last place with 7,500.
</P>
<P>
Eurostat, comparing the first halves of 1996 and 1997, observes
that the most registrations were in Latvia, Lithuania and Slovenia
and the least in Bulgaria, Estonia and Hungary.
</P>
<P>
Figures show that Bulgaria and Romania, where inflation rates
are high, saw a large drop in turnover volume in both the retail
and motor trade between the two periods surveyed.
</P>
<P>
While employment in the motor trade has remained stable, most
countries experienced a decline in retail employment, according to
Eurostat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
