<DOCNO> XIE19980308.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-07 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Appeases Germany Following PM's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 7 (Xinhua) -- Turkey is trying to appease
Germans after remarks by Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz in
an interview with Britain's Financial Times annoyed Bonn, local
newspaper reports said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Umit Pamir, a senior advisor to Yilmaz, was quoted as saying
that the prime minister was misunderstood when he said Germany was
still seeking "Lebensraum," a term used to describe Nazi dictator
Adolf Hitler's aggression polices.
</P>
<P>
He said that what Yilmaz meant with the word was that Germany
is continuing to exploit its "areas of interest," saying that the
prime minister's words had nothing to do with the Nazi period.
</P>
<P>
"The prime minister wanted to pass across the message that
Germany does not give importance to Turkey, but to central and
eastern Europe," Pamir said.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz, who has repeatedly criticized Bonn's policy towards
Turkey, compared the German approach to the European Union (EU)
expansion with Hitler's "Lebensraum" plans, according to the
Financial Times reports.
</P>
<P>
He was also quoted as saying that Germany, the most powerful in
the EU, should be held responsible for the discriminative EU
attitude toward Ankara.
</P>
<P>
The journalists who conducted the interview for the
London-based paper had apparently misunderstood the Turkish prime
minister, Pamir said.
</P>
<P>
German Ambassador to Ankara Hans-Joachim Vergau, when asked to
comment on the reports, said that he did not believe Yilmaz had
said this to the media.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot imagine a responsible politician would resort to
such an ill-considered assault on the honor of the people whose
friendship with Turkey remains irreversible," the German official
said.
</P>
<P>
Ankara was extremely angered by the EU when the EU Luxembourg
summit last December excluded Turkey from the prospective
candidate nations for the upcoming EU enlargement process.
</P>
<P>
The EU leaders held that the serious shortcoming in Turkey's
human rights record, economy as well as tense relations with
neighboring countries made it improper for the involvement in the
current process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
