<HEADLINE> China to Reform Customs Procedures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 8 (Xinhua) -- Director of China's General
Administration of Customs Qian Quanlin today announced that China
will strive to complete the reform on its customs procedures in
three years.
</P>
<P>
The customs office at the Shenzhen Special Economic Zone and
three other customs offices have been designated to experiment
with the reform as from April 1 this year, he said at a penal
discussion of the Ninth National People's Congress now in session
in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The second group of customs offices will be chosen to
experiment with the reform in the latter half of the year.
</P>
<P>
Within this year, China will actively and accurately implement
the relevant policies on preferential taxation, tax reduction or
exemption on the equipment to be imported by domestically-funded
projects, which have been encouraged by the central government for
economic growth, and exempt foreign-funded projects from tariffs
and import-related value-added tax within the scope as prescribed.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, customs offices will continue supporting the
development of the Shenzhen Special Economic Zone, the Pudong New
Area and the Suzhou Industrial Park and open more ports of entry
in the country's central and western and border areas, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the director urged all customs offices to cooperate
still closely with taxation departments in implementing the export
refund system and support the endeavors to increase exports. They
should simplify customs procedures, raise efficiency, cut down the
costs in trading, reform on the related procedures concerning
postal matters and further improve supervision over the exiting
express mails, Qian said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
