<HEADLINE> Mubarak, King Hussein Meet in Cairo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 8 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and
King Hussein of Jordan met here Sunday on propelling the Mideast
peace process and easing the Iraqi-U.N. crisis over arms
inspections.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak met with the Jordanian monarch at a luncheon after
Hussein arrived here Sunday afternoon on a lightning visit to
Egypt, which was decided during a late night telephone
conversation Saturday between them, the Middle East News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
It said that their talks are expected to focus on latest
developments in the region on top of which is the faltering
Mideast peace process notably on the Palestinian-Israeli track and
Arab and international efforts exerted to salvage it.
</P>
<P>
Developments in Iraq and all aspects of Jordanian-Egyptian
relations will also be tackled during Hussein's short visit.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian king, who will visit Washington this week, has
denied that he is commissioned by anybody to propose U.S.-Iraqi
dialog, noting that such a dialog is naturally enough to take
place after Iraq's full abidance by all relevant peace agreements.
</P>
<P>
King Hussein made the statements Saturday after winding up a
Gulf tour. He is expected to brief Mubarak on his talks with the
United Arab Emirates President Sheikh Zayed Bin Sultan Al-Nahyan
and Sultan Qaboos Bin Said of Oman.
</P>
<P>
The king has called on the United States to have a direct
dialogue with Iraq in order to end their standoff.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian monarch is accompanied by a high-level
delegation, including Prime Minister Abdul Salam Majali.
</P>
<P>
The last visit of Hussein to Egypt took place on January
25. 
</P>
