<HEADLINE> U.S., Germany Take Tough Stance on Kosovo Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 8 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright and her German counterpart Klaus Kinkel Sunday agreed to
act swiftly to put an end to the Kosovo conflicts and to force
Belgrade to begin a political dialogue with Kosovo-Albanians.
</P>
<P>
After meeting Kinkel in Bonn Sunday, Albright warned at a news
conference that Washington would stop moves to ease sanctions
against Belgrade unless violence stopped.
</P>
<P>
"The time to stop killings is now before it spreads. The way to
do it is to take an immediate action against Belgrade to ensure
that it pay the price for the damages already done and to
encourage it to finally resolve the problems in Kosovo," Albright
said.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel also stressed that "Everything must be done to ensure
that another awful conflagration do not explode in Europe."
</P>
<P>
Both of them preached a political dialogue between Belgrade and
Kosovo-Albanians with the objective to give Kosovo some form of
self-administration or autonomy.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, both Albright and Kinkel will participate in a
meeting of foreign ministers of the international contact group
for former Yugoslavia in London.
</P>
<P>
According to them, the London meeting will discuss a variety of
measures ranging from economic incentives for Belgrade to threat
of new sanctions. But both of them declined to talk about details.
</P>
<P>
German press quoted diplomatic sources as saying that Albright
would bring a bundle of concrete sanction proposals to the London
conference.
</P>
<P>
Before her short visit to Bonn, Albright also held talks with
Ukrainian and Italian leaders and would make a stop in Paris
before the London conference.
</P>
<P>
In Bonn, the two foreign ministers also discussed the situation
in Iraq. Albright warned that the threat of a U.S. military strike
was not yet over and Iraq's commitment to honoring UN resolutions
for arms inspections had still to be tested.
</P>
<P>
Both ministers also expressed support to reinvigorate the
stalled Middle East peace process, but Albright also said: "It is
ultimately up to the Israeli and Palestinian leaders themselves to
make the hard decisions."  
</P>
