<HEADLINE> Somali Women Call for Implementing Cairo Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, March 8 (Xinhua) -- The Somali women organizations
Sunday called on the warlords to stick to their commitments and
implement the Cairo Peace Accord.
</P>
<P>
At a large demonstration on the eve of the International
Women's Day, Somali women from political factions,
non-governmental organizations (NGOs) and women organizations
urged the politicians to settle Mogadishu's administration
immediately.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of demonstrating women from more than 20
organizations carrying placards and slogans gathered at the
Unknown Soldiers' Monument at the heart of the city where
different speeches were made in commemoration for the Women's day.
</P>
<P>
Hawo Mohamed Ossoble, chairwoman of a local women organization
told the gathering that the faction leaders should now give a
chance to the on-going peace initiatives.
</P>
<P>
"Any further delays to the implementation of the Cairo
agreement is inexcusable," she said.
</P>
<P>
Fadumo Ahmed Qorweyneh who also spoke on the occasion urged
the faction leaders to open the long awaited air and seaports of
the capital.
</P>
<P>
"This would help facilitate the smooth flow of the business
and humanitarian efforts by the international communities," said
Qorweyneh.
</P>
<P>
Also on the occasion, the Save Somali Women and Children
Organization (SSWC) held a performance competition for nine
Somali women poetry. Zakia Abdisalam Alim, Secretary General of
SSWC, said they have also distributed miscellaneous household
utensils to 45 families in three refugee camps in Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
"Somali women are ambitious, " said Alim, adding that "We're
ambitious to restore the rights of the Somali women and take
part in any future administration."
</P>
<P>
During the demonstration co-sponsored by the Coalition
Grassroots Women Organization and the Somali Peace and Human
Rights Network, women groups which celebrated for the first time
in seven years the Women's Day together, also expressed concern
over the very slow pace of the Mogadishu administration. 
</P>
