<HEADLINE> Albania Willing to Allow Kosovo Refugees to Take Shelter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, March 8 (Xinhua) -- Albania could allow ethnic Albanian
refugees in Kosovo to enter the country, but would turn away
certain individuals with terrorist background, government
spokesman Ben Blushi said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time the Albanian government made public its
willingness to accept ethnic Albanian refugees.
</P>
<P>
Albania would not close its border to those threatened by war,
Blushi said, adding that so far, there has been no sign of any
exodus of Kosovo refugees toward the Albanian border.
</P>
<P>
As early as last year, Macedonian President Kirogli Gorov said
if any crisis erupted in Kosovo, Macedonia would like to open a
safety corridor connecting Kosovo and Albania via the country.
</P>
<P>
His proposal was welcomed by Albanian government but was
opposed by leaders of ethnic Albanians in Kosovo, who said they
would never leave their own land.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo was an autonomous province that formed part of Serbia
until 1989 when Serbian authorities revoked the autonomy.
</P>
<P>
Violence in Kosovo has been growing this year following the
non-implementation of an education agreement reached between
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and the leader of ethnic
Albanians, Ibrahim Rugova.
</P>
<P>
Tension heightened there after a Serbian police patrol and
local ethnic Albanians engaged in a fierce cross-fire that killed
four policemen and 16 Albanians on February 28. 
</P>
</TEXT>
