<DOCNO> XIE19980308.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State Enterprise Reform a Step-by-Step Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 8 (Xinhua) -- Intensifying enterprise reform
will result in another 3.5 million workers losing their jobs this
year, making reemployment tougher, according to Chinese Labor
Minister Li Boyong.
</P>
<P>
A total of 11.51 million workers were unemployed at one time
or another last year throughout the country, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Of these laid-off workers, 7.87 million were from state-owned
enterprises, said the minister at a press conference sponsored by
the ongoing annual session of the National People's Congress here
today.
</P>
<P>
While most of the laid-off workers have found new jobs, 4.8
million still need reemployment.
</P>
<P>
The government has been trying hard to expand the coverage of
the existing unemployment insurance system. Factories are required
to contribute more money to unemployment funds; and individual
workers are also asked to contribute to such funds, he said.
</P>
<P>
Currently, factories contribute merely 0.6-1 percent of their
total payroll to the state unemployment fund, and the percentage
is going to be raised to two percent, Li said.
</P>
<P>
According Chen Qingtai, a vice-minister in charge of the State
Economic and Trade Commission, though central planning has been
abandoned in China, the country's industries are still plagued by
inefficiency and overstaffing.
</P>
<P>
"Generally speaking, if a state firm is downsized by one
third,it can still operate smoothly; if downsized by half, its
performance will be better," he said at the same press conference.
</P>
<P>
Reform should be carried out in a step-by-step way, and
society's capability to bear the burden of downsizing should be
taken into consideration, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot simply dump redundant workers onto the society,"
said Chen.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the urgency of enterprise reform, however, and
expressed his belief that conditions are ripe for deepening
reform. 
</P>
</TEXT>
