<HEADLINE> Former Japanese Soldier Testifies About Truth Of War Diary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, March 8 (Xinhua) -- A former Japanese soldier got 10
documents from a notary office here for a lawsuit against Japanese
soldiers who murdered a Chinese during the Nanjing Massacre in
December 1937.
</P>
<P>
Azuma Shiro, who is now 86, got involved in the lawsuit after
he published his diary from World War II a few years ago. Some of
his fellow soldiers sued him for his disclosure about the murder
of a Chinese citizen.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese was put in a mailbag by the soldiers and set on
fire with gasoline, he wrote in his diary, they then strapped
three hand grenades to it and threw it into a pond.
</P>
<P>
A local court in Tokyo decided that Azuma Shiro was telling
lying when it decided that it would be impossible for the soldiers
to hide themselves before the grenades exploded.
</P>
<P>
Experts in Nanjing were asked to test the possibility of such a
thing and found that the soldiers would in fact have had enough
time to get away before the grenades exploded.
</P>
<P>
Nakakita Ryotaro, the former Japanese soldier's lawyer,
confirmed that the tests were done well and that they
substantiated the soldier's story.
</P>
<P>
Azuma Shiro today gave his five-volume diary of more than 2,000
pages together with some badges and army flags he has kept for
decades to Nanjing's Jiangdongmen Memorial Hall. At a ceremony,
the former soldier described his participation in the war and his
time in China, from September 1937 to July 1939, and from March
1944 to August 1945.
</P>
<P>
When he surrendered in Shanghai, he recalls, he met a Chinese
soldier who was a survivor of the Nanjing Massacre who told him,
"I want to kill Japanese prisoners of war whenever I see you, but
the policy does not allow me to do so."
</P>
<P>
He has given the memorial hall permission to publish a Chinese
version of his war diary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
