<HEADLINE> China's Reform Pace-Setter to Make New Contributions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 8 (Xinhua) -- Guangdong Provincial Governor Lu
Ruihua pledged here today that his province would make new
contributions to the nation in the process of continued reform and
opening to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
This year, the 20th anniversary of China's economic reform,
Guangdong will redouble its efforts to maintain its position as a
pace-setter in reform, said Lu, who is here attending the Ninth
National People's Congress in session here since last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong leads the country in terms of gross domestic product,
import and export volume, overseas investment, tax income and
sales of consumer goods, and it has embarked on the road of a
rapid and smooth economic development, he said.
</P>
<P>
The province's economic growth is expected to reach 10 percent
to reach 800 billion yuan this year, he said. If the province
grows at the current pace, it will have realized modernization by
the year 2010, the governor said.
</P>
<P>
To boost agricultural development, Guangdong will work out
regulations and adopt administrative measures to curb the
shrinkage of farmland, he said.
</P>
<P>
On strengthening cooperation between Guangdong and Hong Kong,
the governor said, Guangdong, Hong Kong and Macao traditionally
have a mutually complementary and cooperative relationship. He
expressed the belief that such mutual cooperation will further
strengthen.
</P>
<P>
Owing to the Asian financial crisis, it will be difficult for
Guangdong to increase its exports this year, but the province will
try every possible means to achieve a growth rate of 10 percent in
this field, he said. 
</P>
