<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright, Kinkel Agree on Need to Intervene in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 8 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright and her German counterpart Klaus Kinkel Sunday agreed on
the need to intervene in the Kosovo conflicts.
</P>
<P>
"We agree that everything must be done to ensure that another
conflagration do not explode in Europe.... It is vital to initiate
a dialogue between Belgrade and Kosovo-Albanians on the future of
the region. That is a matter of uttermost urgency," said Kinkel
at a news conference after a meeting with Albright in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
Albright also told reporters that "the time to stop killings is
now before it spreads. The way to do it is to take an immediate
action against Belgrade to ensure that it pay the price for the
damages already done and to encourage it to finally resolve the
problems in Kosovo."
</P>
<P>
Both Albright and Kinkel will participate in a meeting of
foreign ministers of the international contact group Monday in
London.
</P>
<P>
According to them, the London meeting will discuss a series of
measures ranging from economic incentives to threat of sanctions
to force Belgrade to make concession on the Kosovo issue.
</P>
<P>
However, both of them declined to talk about the details.
</P>
<P>
The contact group consists of the United States, Russia,
France, Britain, Germany and Italy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
