<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top Judge Calls for Continued Crackdowns on Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 8 (Xinhua) -- Top judge Ren Jianxin said here
today that China would unswervingly adhere to the principle of
severely cracking down on major crimes according to law, which is
also known as "Strike Hard", to maintain public security.
</P>
<P>
"As a result of constant 'Strike Hard' efforts in these years,
the current overall situation for public security is stable, and
growth in criminal offences has declined," said Ren, president of
the Supreme People's Court, during a panel discussion with the
Shanxi delegation to the ongoing session of the Ninth National
People's Congress, China's top legislature.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, there are still some places where the public
security situation is not good, and just as Premier Li Peng noted
in his government work report to the current NPC session, the
broad masses of the people are still dissatisfied with the current
public security situation.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, we must remain sober-minded and make unremitting
efforts to continue the 'Strike Hard' struggle," he said.
</P>
<P>
He urged all judicial bodies to firmly implement the principle
of cracking down fast, heavily and in accordance with law on
crimes seriously harming public security, wipe out social evils
like pornography, gambling and drugs, and fight against corruption
in a down-to-earth manner by severely punishing criminals in cases
of embezzlement and bribery.
</P>
<P>
Law enforcement departments should also resolutely combat
economic crimes, such as sabotaging financial order and tax
collection, smuggling, and producing and selling fake and shoddy
goods, he noted.
</P>
<P>
"We must punish crimes, protect the people and provide them
with a stable work, study and living environment," he concluded.
</P>
</TEXT>
