<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Opposition Party Returns to Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 8 (Xinhua) -- The major opposition Bangladesh
Nationalist Party (BNP) returned to the Jatiya Sangsad
(parliament) Sunday afternoon following a six-month abstention
since August 30 last year.
</P>
<P>
The parliamentary crisis, which arose out of continued boycott
by the opposition, was put to an end when the ruling Awami League
and the BNP reached an agreement on March 2, which was endorsed by
the BNP Parliamentary Party Saturday evening.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the result of a four-day negotiation, the
ruling party agreed to withdraw before March 31 "all the
politically motivated cases" filed against BNP lawmakers, leaders
and party workers after investigations, and the opposition would
return to the parliament.
</P>
<P>
"All the 113 BNP members of parliament shall be inducted in
parliamentary standing committees on 35 ministries," the agreement
said.
</P>
<P>
The parliament might witness heated debate on the Chittagong
Hill Tracts agreement, which the government and the tribal rebels
signed last December and has attracted strong attacks from the
opposition, reports said.
</P>
<P>
At a public meeting on Saturday evening, Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina thanked the opposition party for its decision to return to
parliament.
</P>
<P>
She said she hoped the BNP would play its due role in making
the parliament effective and meaningful.
</P>
<P>
The Jatiya Sangsad was the center of all activities where all
national issues could be sorted out through debate and discussion,
she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
