<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 8 (Xinhua) -- The following are major business
briefs from the Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The total budget deficit of the Gulf Cooperation
Council (GCC) states dropped to 10 billion U.S. dollars in 1996
from 20 billion dollars in 1993, Egyptian newspaper Today's
World reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The GCC states, which group Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar,
Bahrain and the United Arab Emirates, had worked out programs
designed to eliminate their deficits by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The 31st Cairo International Fair will open on
Wednesday with up to 3,500 Egyptian and foreign companies
participating.
</P>
<P>
As many as 1,000 foreign companies will showcase their products
at the exhibition, which will provide investors with potential
opportunities to enhance their contribution to the development in
Egypt.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- The Gulf Arab oil-producing countries will intensify
their consultations with the aim of finding means to halt the
decline of oil prices in the world markets.
</P>
<P>
Gulf sources believed that it was unlikely for oil officials of
the six GCC states to meet soon before the proposed emergency
conference of OPEC member states in a bid to end the constant
decline of oil prices in the world market which has a direct and
considerable effect on the budgets of the GCC states.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- A delegation from the Kuwait Airways Corporation
started talks in Amman, the capital of Jordan, Saturday with
officials of the General Organization of the Royal Jordanian
Airline on ways of rectifying the flights between Jordan and
Kuwait, which resumed last summer.
</P>
<P>
The talks will also deal with the possibility of redoubling the
flights between Jordan and Kuwait - which are four flights a week
at present - to meet the growing demand for travelling by plane
between the two countries, especially during the summer months.
</P>
