<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Science Quality" Should Be Improved in China: Scientist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 8 (Xinhua) -- It is of great urgency to enhance
the "science quality" of the Chinese nation, a member of China's
top advisory body said here today.
</P>
<P>
Liu Shu, a member of the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference (CPPCC) National Committee, which is in
session here, urged the government to increase investment in
spreading popular scientific knowledge and building more
scientific facilities.
</P>
<P>
The science-related quality of a nation covers three aspects:
understanding of scientific terms and concepts, understanding of
the process and methods of scientific researches and understanding
of the impact of science on social development, he said.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey conducted by the China Association for Science
and Technology (CAST) shows that 25 percent of the people aged
between 18 and 69 surveyed have never heard of the word
"molecule," nor have 45 percent of them any idea of what DNA is.
</P>
<P>
"What worries me most is that the recent survey has almost the
same result as the one conducted in 1992," said Liu, who is also
CAST vice chairman.
</P>
<P>
In terms of people's "science quality", China legs far behind
the United States, Japan and European countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
The most fundamental factor affecting a nation's "science
quality" is the level of education its people receive, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said governments at all levels in China should give priority
to the development of education and quicken the pace of illiteracy
elimination.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, nine-year compulsory
education is now universally provided in 65 percent of areas in
China. The percentage is expected to go up to 72 percent this
year.
</P>
<P>
At present, six percent of Chinese adults are illiterate. The
state strives to help 3.5 million young and middle-aged
illiterates learn to read and write this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
