<HEADLINE> NPC Deputies Call for Legislation on Non-public-owned Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 8 (Xinhua) -- Some deputies to the Ninth
National People's Congress (NPC) suggested that legislative work
be strengthened so as to ensure the sound growth of
non-public-owned economy.
</P>
<P>
NPC deputies Chen Hong and Liao Changguang, both from the
newly-founded Chongqing Municipality, have taken the lead in
submitting a motion on the legislation concerning the
non-public-owned economic sector to the ongoing First Session of
the Ninth NPC.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, more than 100 NPC deputies from different places and
trades have signed on the motion. According to Chinese law, a
motion with more than 30 signatures will be valid.
</P>
<P>
Chen Hong, chairman of the Chongqing Municipal Federation of
Industry and Commerce, said the legislation will be aimed at
standardizing the growth of non-public-owned economic sector,
protecting its legal rights and interests, clarifying its social
responsibilities, creating a more relaxed environment for it, and
make it cope with the demand of building the market economy with
Chinese characteristics.
</P>
<P>
The existing laws are not able to meet the need of this
economic sector's development, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
According to the statistics provided by Chen Hong, there had
been more than 960,000 private businesses across China by the end
of 1997, which employed 13.5 million people and involved fixed
assets totaling 514 billion yuan (61.9 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The total output value of these businesses in 1997 reached
392.2 billion yuan (47.25 billion US dollars), and their combined
business income amounted to 309.6 billion yuan (37.3 billion US
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The 15th National Congress of the Communist Party of China
(CPC), held in last fall, has made it clear that the
non-public-owned economic sector has contributed significantly to
the national economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
