<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Delegation Comments Favorably On China's Village Election (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, March 8 (Xinhua) -- A visiting delegation from the
U.S.'s Carter Center has witnessed a village committee in
northeast China's Jilin Province and heard an explanation by local
officials about how it works.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Robert Pastor, the head of the 10-member delegation, which
stood in a piercing cold wind for five hours to witness the
election process in the village of Gujialingzi, commented that he
has seen a lot of elections in many countries but has never seen
government officials doing the job so seriously.
</P>
<P>
One of the candidates for village leader, Liu Fu, a bean curd
maker, promised in his speech to teach his people the skills for
making bean curd free of charge, if he is elected head of the
village.
</P>
<P>
"Promising is one thing, but doing a good job is another
thing," was the response of one villager who asked not to be
identified and who took exception with Liu's promise.
</P>
<P>
The village committee is a grass-roots organization in rural
China with a rural population of 900 million, and a direct
election system in one million villages was introduced in 1988.
</P>
<P>
Zhan Chengfu, a Civil Affairs Ministry official in charge of
political power at the grass-roots level, points out that
fundamental changes have taken place in choosing village committee
members in recent years, having gone from administrative
appointment to direct election. And election methods have changed,
from a village Party committee nominating the candidates to giving
complete freedom to nominate candidates to the villagers.
</P>
</TEXT>
