<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian, Canadian Win HK Int'l Golden Mile Races </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 8 (Xinhua) -- Anthony Hill of Australia and
Canada's Cindy O'Krane won the men's and women's international
races at the 13th annual Hong Kong International Golden Mile races
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Hill, 26, clocked a title-winning time of four minutes 10
seconds in the men's race, eight seconds slower than his personal
best time.
</P>
<P>
He was followed by Canada's pre-race favorite Allan Klassen in
4:12 and British Joseph Mills, who clocked 4:14.
</P>
<P>
Hill, ranked third back in Australia, said the victory "paid
off" the painstaking efforts he had made. He had to recover from
injuries he had suffered during the 1995 race here when he was
sixth.
</P>
<P>
He said he enjoyed the race, the first major race for him this
season. Praising the crowd "very inspiring", he said he would try
to come back next year.
</P>
<P>
O'Krane, a Canadian debutante at the race, clocked 4:41 to take
the women's race.
</P>
<P>
Liu Haiyan from Guangdong, China, was second in the close chase
by clocking 4:42 and Indonesia's Supriyati Sutono finished third
in 4:48.
</P>
<P>
The 35-year-old O'Krane said the win was not easy. "There are
many sharp corners which is really challenging to me. If not with
those corners, I would have run faster," she said.
</P>
<P>
Liu Haiyan, who finished third in last year's race here, said
she had made a tactical mistake in the race by running too slow in
the early stages.
</P>
<P>
"I really should take the lead but poor pre-race training made
me decide just to follow others in the first," the 24-year-old
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
