<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Five West Africans Arrested in Zambia for Cheat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 8 (Xinhua) -- Five west Africans have been
arrested by Zambian police for cheating a local businessman of 45
million Kwacha (30,000 U.S. Dollars) in a deal to counterfeit 3
million dollars, reported the Sunday Times of Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The five suspects were picked up by Zambian police last
Thursday in Lusaka, police service spokesman Beenwell Chimfwembe
said Saturday, adding that three of them are from Senegal, Ivory
Coast, Guinea respectively and the other two claimed to be from
Liberia.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian businessman was cheated in a lucrative deal. The
conmen promised to reward him handsomely once he gave them the
money to acquire chemicals to be used to counterfeit the 3
million fake dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, the deal turned sour when the five suspects got away
with the businessman's money.
</P>
<P>
The five initially approached the man with a package
containing papers that they claimed, came from the U.S. and
contained three million dollars in paper form, said the
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
They told the businessman that the papers can turn into U.S.
Dollars once processed in chemicals.
</P>
<P>
The conmen dubiously processed a $10 and a $20 note to convice
the man and assured him of five percent of the 3 million dollars
once he gave 45 million Kwacha for chemicals.
</P>
<P>
The local businessman gave them the money and withheld the
package containing the purported 3 million dollars as surety that
they would come.
</P>
<P>
He reported the case to the police last Thusday after the five
disappeared.
</P>
<P>
Some more people are belived to be involved into the case and
the investigations are still under way, said the police
spokesman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
