<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Expects Relief to Fuel Scarcity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 8 (Xinhua) -- The wide fuel scarcity in
oil-producing Nigeria is expected to be partly relieved Tuesday,
when a major refinery in the southern city of Port Harcourt
resumes production after maintenance.
</P>
<P>
The management of the Port Harcourt Refinery said this at the
weekend, when Musa Sheshu, Administrator of the Rivers
State, paid a visit to the refinery.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria, Africa's top oil producer with a daily crude oil
production of over two million barrels, has been suffering from
persistent fuel shortage due to the poor performances of its four
major refineries.
</P>
<P>
Turn-around-maintenance of the refineries have been overdue
for years but work could not be started for lack of funds.
</P>
<P>
The Port Harcourt refinery, with a daily processing capacity
of 150,000 barrels, was shut down in mid-February due to a major
equipment failure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
