<HEADLINE> International Seminar on Ganges Barrage Begins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 8 (Xinhua) -- A three-day international seminar on
the feasibility of the proposed Ganges Barrage project in
Bangladesh started here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"We want to ensure the welfare of the country and its people
through proper management and development of the water resources
of Bangladesh," Prime Minster Sheikh Hasina said while
inaugurating the seminar.
</P>
<P>
The 30-year Ganges water sharing treaty her government signed
with India in 1996 had opened the opportunity of undertaking
projects for the development of the Ganges water resources, she
said.
</P>
<P>
"We intend to act now on the best possible option...for
improving the life and livelihood for our people on the water of
the Ganges," she said.
</P>
<P>
The seminar, on "water resources management and development in
Bangladesh with particular reference to the Ganges River," was
attended by some 150 delegates, including 59 from foreign
countries and international organizations.
</P>
<P>
The main objective of the seminar, jointly organized by the
Bangladesh Water Resources Ministry, the Japanese government, the
World Bank, and the Asian Development Bank, was free exchange of
views among experts and government officials to find out common
terms and conditions to build the barrage.
</P>
<P>
The much-talked-about barrage near Bhanga, Faridpur, some 112
kilometers northwest of here, has been planned for protecting the
southwest region of the country which reports said has been
seriously affected by the Farakka Barrage of India.
</P>
<P>
Officials said the barrage was needed to utilize the Ganges
water properly, after the signing of the Ganges water sharing
treaty, to protect the world's largest mangrove forest of
Sundarban, maintain environmental balance and ensure
socio-economic development in the southwestern region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
