<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Fuel-to-Oil Giant Weighs Arabian Oil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 8 (Xinhua) -- OBSOL, the oil-from-coal
giant in South Africa, is studying two foreign projects to
convert gas to liquid fuels, local daily Sunday Times reported.
</P>
<P>
SASOL is expected to make the decision in the next two to
three months as to whether to go ahead with a 24 billion Rand
(2.8 billion U.S. Dollars) diesel-from-gas project in the Middle
East.
</P>
<P>
Using its locally developed slurry phase distillate process,
the plant could be in full operation by 2003, producing 20,000
barrels a day at Rass Laffan in eastern Qatar, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The project also involves the state-owned Qatar General
Petroleum Corporation which will have a 51 percent interest in
the operation and provide the natural gas, while the U.S. based
Phillips Petroleum Company with 14 percent, will provide
marketing expertise.
</P>
<P>
SASOL will hold 35 percent and provide the technology.
</P>
<P>
The process will produce a synthetic diesel fuel with superior
characteristics to those of conventional fuels, free of sulphur,
low in aromatics and with lower emission levels.
</P>
<P>
"It will be the first major venture to convert natural gas to
liquid fuels and could be used in other parts of the world
because it is environmentally friendly," said SASOL managing
director Pieter Cox.
</P>
<P>
Also under investigation is a project to convert gas into
crude oil and liquid fuels with Statoil of Norway. Statoil has
substantial gas reserves in the North Sea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
