<HEADLINE> Marriages Between Unproportionally Aged People in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 8 (Xinhua) - Unproportional age group
marriages between girls and men have lowered the family planning
rate in Tanzania to 12 percent, an official said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Catherine Sanga, Assistant Manager of the National Family
Planning Project, told a workshop here that as a common practice
in which many girls married older men qualified to be their
grandfathers, such kind of couples don't discuss family planning
matters.
</P>
<P>
"Studies have revealed that over 50 percent of couples in
Tanzania don't discuss reproductive health or particularly family
planning issues in their life," she said.
</P>
<P>
Though family planning was accepted at the highest 23.7
percent in the Kilimanjaro Region, she said, the Shinyanga Region
was at the ebb with only 4.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Sanga called on the government to update the Marriage Law so
as to safeguard teenage girls against the risks of marrying old
men because it is unsafe as their children's supporting hip bones
are not fully matured till they reach the age of 20.
</P>
<P>
"Adolescent marriages and exposure to unsafe sex have led the
maternal deaths rate risen to alarming levels of from 500 to 700
per 100,000 live births," she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
