<HEADLINE> Hostage Drama Ends in Southern Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 8 (Xinhua) -- The four-day hostage drama in the
Reception and Diagnostic Center of the Davao Penal Colony in
Kapalong, the Southern Philippines, ended Sunday following a
police assault on eight inmates who had been holding five women
since Thursday.
</P>
<P>
All hostage-takers were accounted for after a three-minute
police raid, the official Philippine News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
The agency said that the anti-terrorist team members from the
regional police mobile force disguised before the assault as food
servers to both hostage-takers and hostages.
</P>
<P>
However, it said, the hostages were hurt in the raid as they
were pushed out of the center area.
</P>
<P>
They were stabbed by the abductors led by Dario Mahumot, who
violently reacted to the blazing guns of the raiding team, which
was assisted by the Criminal Investigation Service Command, the
agency said.
</P>
<P>
Mrs. Paulina Corda, chief of the center, was in critical
condition as she was brought down to the Davao Medical Center in
Davao City, along with four other hostages aboard a Philippine
Airforce helicopter, it said.
</P>
<P>
The eight inmates took hostages the five women employees of the
Davao Penal Colony Thursday morning, demanding safe passage to the
rebel Moro Islamic Liberation Front's camp, the ouster of the
prison superintendent and the construction of a mosque in the
colony. 
</P>
</TEXT>
