<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-08 09:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qatar: Oil Price Slump Imposes No Threat to OPEC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, March 8 (Xinhua) -- Qatar's Oil Minister Abdullah
bin Hamad Al-Attiyah has said that the current oil price slump
would not impose any threat to the future of the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC).
</P>
<P>
Qatar's Oil Minister was quoted Sunday by the official Qatari
news agency (QNA) as saying that "the present (price) crisis will
not lead to the collapse of OPEC."
</P>
<P>
Al-Attiyah said that OPEC "is a very important organization to
the oil market even from the psychological point of view."
</P>
<P>
Al-Attiyah on Thursday warned other OPEC oil ministers against
hurrying into an emergency meeting this month without careful
preparations on how the group could rescue sagging oil prices.
</P>
<P>
The prices have lost by more than 30 percent to the current 14
dollars a barrel due to abundant supplies and declined demand
caused by a mild winter in the northern hemisphere and Asia's
economic turmoil.
</P>
<P>
The ample supplies was triggered by OPEC's November decision
to raise its combined output ceiling by 10 percent to 27.5
million barrels per day, and compounded by consistent quota
violations by some OPEC members.
</P>
<P>
OPEC's Secretary General Riwanu Lukman has invited the
group's 11 members to attend a scheduled four-man monitoring
committee meeting to discuss ways of propping up oil prices.
</P>
<P>
But experts predict that the meeting will fail to reach any
substantial breakthrough to tackle the slump in prices due to
the reluctance of the majority of the bloc's members to trim
their output quotas.
</P>
<P>
Venezuela, OPEC's biggest quota buster has said publicly that
it would not cut output by even one barrel to turn the market
around if other members take the lead. Saudi Arabia, Iran and
Kuwait have also refused to become the first to lead in reining in
production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980308.0103 </DOCNO>
