<DOCNO> XIE19980308.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oil-for-Food Deal Very Temporary Measure: Iraqi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 8 (Xinhua)-- Iraqi Oil Minister Amir Mohammed
Rasheed said on Saturday that Iraq wants lifting of U.N. sanctions
instead of the oil-for-food deal, a very temporary measure.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with Xinhua, Rasheed said
oil-for-food deal under U.N. Security Council resolution 986,
which allows Iraq to sell limited amount of oil to buy food and
medicine, was temporary measure supposed to be for only six
months.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, the deal has existed for three years
instead of six months.
</P>
<P>
"We work with it, we facilitate its implementation, but it
is temporary measure. The proper measure is the lifting of all
sanctions, which we deserve fully," he said.
</P>
<P>
Rasheed, top negotiator in talks with the U.N. Special
Commission charged of disarming Iraq of its weapons of mass
destruction, said the United States intended to make oil-for-food
deal a sort of permanent measure, so that iraq can only buy
consuming items.
</P>
<P>
What the United States wants to see is that "Iraq cannot
build its health infrastructure, it cannot build its agricultural,
industrial, educational and oil infrastructure, so that it doesn't
develop its capability as a society," said Rasheed.
</P>
<P>
Under the first and second phases of oil-for-food deal, Iraq
was allowed to sell 2 billion U.S. dollars worth of oil every six
months to buy humanitarian supplies for its people.
</P>
<P>
A new U.N. Security Council resolution adopted last month
allows Iraq to pump 5.2 billion dollars worth of oil in six
months in the third phase which started from last December.
</P>
<P>
However, Iraq has said it is unable to pump oil of more
than 4 billions dollars in six months.
</P>
<P>
Rasheed said there are two reasons behind its unability to
pump that much oil. First, the decline of oil prices. He
said in the first phase of oil-for-food deal, oil price was
18 dollars per barrel; now it is just more than 11 dollars
per barrel and the price is coming down.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, it is the lack of spare parts and chemical
material. "American position within the U.N. Sanctions Committee
was to refuse all the contracts we have presented to them for
approval. They have been holding them now for more than one year,
we only got very, very little amount of spare parts," he said.
</P>
<P>
Rasheed said that Iraq has agreed to receiving oil experts sent
by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan to Iraq next week.
</P>
<P>
"We will define with them our requirement in terms of spare
parts and chemical material, so we can increase oil export," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said Iraq now can pump 3 million barrels of oil per day and
consumes 0.7 million barrels, so it can only export more than 2
million barrels. "We will explain this to oil experts that there will
be quite a few hundred of millions of dollars we need to the
minimum," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
