<HEADLINE> West Knows Little of Religious Affairs in China: Bishop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 8 (Xinhua) -- Countries in the West know very
little about religious affairs in China, according to a well-known
religious figure.
</P>
<P>
"For Western countries, their knowledge of religious matters in
China has remained to be that of 20 years ago," said Fu Tieshan,
head of the Chinese Patriotic Catholic Association and bishop of
the Beijing Diocese, in an interview. Fu is currently attending
the annual session of the Chinese legislature as a deputy here.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese government pursues a policy of religious
freedom," he said. "At present, there are more than 100 million
religious believers throughout the country."
</P>
<P>
He said that since the end of the 1970s, more than 5,000
catholic churches have been restored.
</P>
<P>
"I'm pious to God when I participate in the administration of
state affairs," said the 66-year-old Fu.
</P>
<P>
Fu said the common task for the country's five religions,
namely Buddism, Taoism, Catholicism, Christianity and Islam, is to
adapt the religions to socialism, China's national conditions and
the Chinese culture.
</P>
<P>
"People may believe in the same God, but the methods of worship
should be different in accordance with difference national
conditions," he said, adding that support from religious circles
is needed for reform, development and stability in China.
</P>
<P>
"Also," he said, "religious development would suffer if the
Chinese economy and society should get into trouble." 
</P>
</TEXT>
