<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deteriorating Students Health Situation in S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 8 (Xinhua) -- All students in a high
school in Soweto, Johannesburg, were found to be HIV-positive,
and as a result, health authorities had to destroy about 400
liters of contaminated blood taken from the pupils, City Press
weekly reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
About 920 students at the school are infected with the human
immuno-deficiency virus, which will lead to the deadly disease of
AIDS, the paper said. But it did not name the school in the
largest black township in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted sources as saying that the contamination
is a major problem faced by the South African Blood Transfusion
Service, which invariably stumbled upon liters of infected blood
each time they tried to replenish the blood bank.
</P>
<P>
"We haven't spoken to the press about this incident because
AIDS stigmatizes," the paper quoted one source as saying.
</P>
<P>
The implication is that the HIV/AIDS epidemic is rampant in
South Africa and runs deeper than people want to believe, said
the paper.
</P>
<P>
Published figures of South Africans infected by the HIV/AIDS
epidemic at the moment range between 2.2 million and 3.5 million.
Working on these figures means between 220,000 and 350,000 South
Africans, especially young people, will die each year for the
next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Health Minister Nkosazana Zuma said last month that the
disease is "gnawing away at our population," with 1,500 people
now infected every day.
</P>
<P>
A South African life insurer, Southern Life, predicted last
year that 25 percent of South Africans will be HIV-positive by
the year 2005. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
