<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Worker Participation Urged in Reform of State Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 8 (Xinhua) -- A high-ranking Chinese leader
called for the participation of workers in reform of state
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
"Opinions of workers must be solicited on major issues of
enterprise reform, and reform schemes must be submitted to
workers' congresses for prior approval," said Wei Jianxing, a
Standing Committee member of the Politburo of the Communist Party
of China (CPC) Central Committee, in a group discussion attended
by deputies from Heilongjiang Province to the National People's
Congress (NPC), in session here since last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"It is necessary to guard against the erroneous practice of a
few leading officials deciding to merge or sell an enterprise
without consulting workers before hand," Wei said.
</P>
<P>
"This is not merely an issue of procedure or working methods,"
he said. "It concerns the result of state firm reform and social
stability."
</P>
<P>
Leading cadres of debt-ridden enterprises must keep the style
of hard struggle and plain living and should set examples by
sharing hardships as well as comforts with the masses, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We will never allow a few leading cadres of enterprises to
squander money and live in extravagance, or even seek personal
gains by abusing their powers, while some workers are laid off and
live a difficult life," he said.
</P>
<P>
The senior Party official noted that the organization and
readjustment of leadership lineup in state firms must be based on
popular agreement from workers and the system of evaluating
leading cadres of enterprises annually by workers must be
maintained. 
</P>
</TEXT>
