LUSAKA, March 8 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Zambia (BOZ), a
central bank, is establishing a deposit protection scheme for
savers, a measure designed to protect depositors in the event of
a bank failure, Times of Zambia reported sunday.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed Saturday in Lusaka by Abraham Mwenda, BOZ
deputy governor in charge of operations.
</P>
<P>
When discussing at a fund-raising dinner the impact of bank
closures on the economy and steps the central bank is taking to
arrest the situation, Mwenda said the scheme is one of the
central bank's measures to improve the country's banking
industry.
</P>
<P>
However, Mwenda gave no further details on the scheme.
</P>
<P>
The BOZ is also revising the country's 1994 Bank and Financial
Services Act by introducing additional regulations that are aimed
at empowering the central bank to swiftly deal with ailing banks,
improve corporate governance in banks and ensure that managers
run their banks prudently.
</P>
<P>
As for the argument by some quarters that the banking industry
is collapsing, the deputy governor said it is an exaggerated
assertion with no firm basis whatsoever.
</P>
<P>
He said the size of the banking sector has remained largely
unaffected as the banks that have gone under accounted for only
five percent of the industry's assets.
</P>
<P>
Although confidence in local small banks has been severely
eroded, this is not the case for the entire banking system,
Mwenda stressed.
</P>
<P>
He also assured that monetary authorities and the Zambian
government will remain committed to the pursuit of prudent fiscal
and monetary policies which will contain bank failures which
Zambia suffered much in the past year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
