<HEADLINE> Xinjiang People Aspiring for Stability, Development: Official (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 8 (Xinhua) -- Social stability, ethnical unity
and economic growth are the aspirations sought after by the 16
million people of various ethnic groups in the Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region, chairman of the regional people's government
said.
</P>
<P>
The aspirations are a driving force to promote the reform and
opening-up of Xinjiang, said Ablait Abdurexit, chairman of the
autonomous regional people's government who is here attending
the First Session of the Ninth National People's Congress as an
NPC deputy.
</P>
<P>
He called on regional officials to take active measures to
safeguard social stability and boost economic development.
</P>
<P>
"At the time being, Xinjiang witnesses a stable situation,
rapid economic growth and marked improvement in the local people's
living standards," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Our goal is that people of all ethnic groups in Xinjiang will
lead a fairly comfortable life by the end of the century, and this
year will be crucial for Xinjiang's development," the 56-year-old
chairman said.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Xinjiang's agriculture scored bumper harvest for the
20th year in a row, the per capita income of farmers rose by 17
percent over the previous year, and the total industrial output
value increased by 13 percent which was higher than the national
average.
</P>
<P>
For the first time, the autonomous region's fiscal revenue
exceeded 10 billion yuan (1.2 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
At present, the central government is giving more support to
the country's western areas including Xinjiang to promote local
industry, infrastructure, finance, loans and opening-up. "We will
seize the opportunity and turn Xinjiang's advantage in resources
into an economic edge," Ablait said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980308.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-08 </DATE_TIME>
