<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers Call for Tighter Control of Auto Exhaust </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 8 (Xinhua) -- Some Chinese legislators worried
by the country's worsening air pollution have called for tighter
control over exhaust emissions from cars through law amendments
and administrative measures.
</P>
<P>
"The number of motor vehicles in some large and medium-sized
cities has surged in recent years, and air pollution caused by
auto emissions is damaging urban environment and harming people's
health," said Cao Youxuan, a deputy to the Ninth National People's
Congress, in session here since last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
China now has approximately 13 million motor vehicles, and the
number is expected to exceed 20 million by 2000.
</P>
<P>
Urban air quality reports regularly released by the National
Environmental Protection Agency show that auto emissions have
become a main source of air pollution in some major cities.
</P>
<P>
Environmental experts estimate that the annual emission of
harmful gas by motor vehicles across China can reach tens of
millions of tons.
</P>
<P>
Though a law was enacted on air pollution prevention in 1987,
Cao said, the law mainly aims at curbing pollution caused by coal
burning, and can't effectively control auto emissions.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he said, the law only stipulates that enterprises
and social institutions will be punished for polluting the air,
while owners of private cars seem to be exempt from any penalties
even if their vehicles have caused pollution.
</P>
<P>
He said that he has won the support of dozens of his fellow
lawmakers to submit a proposal to the ongoing First Session of the
Ninth NPC, asking for an amendment to the law.
</P>
<P>
He also urged relevant government departments and auto makers
to work out stricter standards for auto emissions, carry out more
inspections, and impose more severe punishment on owners of
vehicles that fail to meet standards.
</P>
<P>
As a result of growing public complaints, the government in
recent years has paid increasing attention to air pollution caused
by motor vehicles. Use of leaded gas has been forbidden in several
cities including Beijing and Shanghai. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
