<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weed Chemical Causes Reproductive Defects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 8 (Xinhua) -- The chemical 2.4D, that will be
sprayed in Lake Kariba in north Zimbabwe to destroy the
fast-spreading water weed, causes reproductive defects in both
humans and animals, the Sunday Mail reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Lake Kariba, now heavily polluted as a result of direct
inflows of raw sewage from hotels or lodges and from Nyamhunga
and Mahombekombe townships, had been invaded by water hyacinth, a
noxious weed.
</P>
<P>
The weed, now covering about 80 percent of the lake, which is
a source of hydro-electricity for both Zimbabwe and Zambia, was
being fed by nutrients in the lake.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Biological scientists of the University of
Zimbabwe as saying that 2.4D reduced male hormones in those who
drank the contaminated water.
</P>
<P>
In the long term, the paper said, this often resulted in
population losses as has happened in some western European
countries now frantically trying to bring up their population by
offering "incentives"' to couples who bore children.
</P>
<P>
The chemical, also known as "gender bender", had the potential
of interfering with sexual hormones resulting in low sperm count
in males. This had the long term effect of causing barrenness.
</P>
<P>
Professor Chris Magadza, scientist and researcher with the
Department of Biological Sciences of the University of Zimbabwe,
said the loss of the male species occurred even among the fish.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary research had indicated that there were lots of
female fish species in Lake Chivero near Harare as the males had
either low sperm count to fertilize or had become unproductive,
he said.
</P>
<P>
"In some fish populations it has been seen that there are no
males at all," said Magadza, who together with his team of
scientists, has undertaken extensive research on the effects of
pollution and industrial effluent into Lake Chivero and Lake
Kariba. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
