<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Three Gorges Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 8 (Xinhua) -- Following is a brief introduction
to the Three Gorges Water Control Project mentioned in Chinese
Premier Li Peng's government work report to the First Session of
the Ninth National People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
The Three Gorges Water Control Project is a key state project
for harnessing the Yangtze River, the world's third longest, in a
comprehensive way. It has many functions including flood control,
power generation and facilitation of shipping on the river. It is
divided into three parts -- construction of a dam, resettlement of
affected people and power generation.
</P>
<P>
The water control project, located near Yichang, central
China's Hubei Province, is the largest project ever built in China
and one of the 1,500 largest projects in the world. It has a
budgetary estimate of 50.09 billion yuan (calculated according to
May, 1993 prices).
</P>
<P>
Upon completion, the hydropower station is to have 26
generating units with a combined installed capacity of 18.2
million kw and an annual electricity output of 84.7 billion kwh,
making it the biggest hydropower station in the world. The Yangtze
River was dammed at the project site on November 8, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Resettlement of affected people started in October 1992. The
entire project is scheduled for completion in the year 2009.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980308.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Xiaolangdi Water Control Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 8 (Xinhua) -- Following is a brief introduction
to the Xiaolangdi Water Control Project mentioned in Chinese
Premier Li Peng's government work report to the First Session of
the Ninth National People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
The Xiaolangdi Water Control Project is the largest of its kind
on the Yellow River. In terms of workload, it is second only to
the Three Gorges Project on the Yangtze.
</P>
<P>
The project, located 40 km north of the ancient city of Luoyang
in central China's Henan Province, controls an encatchment of
694,000 sq km, 92.3 percent of the total along the Yellow River.
</P>
<P>
It aims to prevent flooding and ice runs as well as to reduce
silting. It will also have the functions of water supply,
irrigation and power generation.
</P>
<P>
Its estimated cost is around 40 billion yuan, and there is a
plan to use more than one billion U.S. dollars in overseas-sourced
funds. The Yellow River was dammed at the project site on October
28, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the project started in September 1991 and is
scheduled for completion in the year 2001. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
