<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing's Environment Better Than Reported </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 8 (Xinhua) -- The quality of environment in the
Chinese capital keeps improving, not deteriorating, said a Chinese
environmental scientist here today.
</P>
<P>
"What overseas media has reported on Beijing's deteriorating
environment are exaggeration," said Jiang Xiaoke, chairperson of
Beijing Environmental Science Society.
</P>
<P>
Jiang, who is a female deputy to the First Session of the Ninth
National People's Congress (NPC), said chimneys were seen emitting
black smoke anywhere in Beijing but such scenes are rare today.
</P>
<P>
Seniorer residents remember very well that they had to wear
gauze masks and scarves to cover up their faces whenever they went
outside, but there is no such a need now, said Jiang, who is also
president of Beijing Environmental Protection Foundation.
</P>
<P>
She quoted the monitoring results as saying that dust pollution
has kept reducing year by year. The discharge of sulphur dioxide
remained the same level as before. She acknowledged that exhaust
discharge by motor vehicles poses a new hazard.
</P>
<P>
The expert said air pollution in Beijing has been mainly
produced by coal burning, which produced a lot of sulphur dioxide
and dust. Some 27 million tons of coal is burnt annually in
Beijing. But the supply of the piped natural gas from northwest
China will help cope with this problem, she said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Jiang said, pollution control in the capital's large
enterprises has paid off. the Capital Steel Complex (or Shougang
Company Group), 30 km west of Beijing, injected 100 million yuan
of funding for pollution control last year, and the Beijing
Chemical Industry Group, another major polluter in Beijing, has
resorted to the use of loans from the World Bank in pollution
control, he said.
</P>
<P>
Another major measure is to introduce lead-free oil as fuel
construct a number of sewage disposal and garbage burying plants,
she said.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, Beijing plans to increase 520 ha of green land in
urban areas and add 28,000 ha of woods on its outskirts, she said.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, Beijing remains to be one of the world's most
polluted cities, which is attributed to its natural conditions as
well as an issue left over by history, Jiang said. And more time
is need to bring the city's pollution under complete control.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
