<HEADLINE> Diplomacy Seen as Possible way to Solve Kosovo Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, March 7 (Xinhua) -- The United States and Italy still see
diplomacy as the possible means to solve the crisis in the
province where violent conflict between ethnic Albanians and
Serbian police erupted on March 1, U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright said here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Albright made the remarks during a joint press conference with
her Italian counterpart Lamberto Dini after she wound up a two-day
visit Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders will attend a conference convened by the
Contact Group for ex-Yugoslavia in London on Monday to put
together a diplomatic strategy.
</P>
<P>
Describing the situation in the region as "very worrying," Dini
said Kosovo should be given back its autonomy, which it had
enjoyed until 1989.
</P>
<P>
Ethnic Albanians, who make up 90 percent of the population of
Kosovo, have been seeking independence since early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Albright and Dini also discussed Iran's new moderate positions.
</P>
<P>
Dini, who was in Tehran last weekend, said it is time for the
U.S. and other Western countries to "restore relations" with the
country.
</P>
<P>
As the first senior Western leader to visit the country since
President Mohammad Khatami was elected, Dini noted that the new
Iranian government is different from its predecessors, and that
Western countries should grasp the opportunity to alter their
policies toward Iran. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980308.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former SS Officers Receive Life Sentences </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, March 7 (Xinhua) -- The Italian military court of appeal
Saturday handed down life-sentences to two former SS officers in
connection with a Massacre in Rome during the Second World War.
</P>
<P>
Erich Priebke and Karl Hass, both in their mid-80s, were
involved in the massacre known as the Ardeatine Caves atrocities
in 1944, in which 335 men and boys were rounded up and shot dead
on Rome's outskirts in reprisal for a partisan bomb that killed 33
German soldiers in the city.
</P>
<P>
The two defendants were not on hand for the reading of the
sentences, which was greeted by cheers and applause from the
audience.
</P>
<P>
The appeal hearing opened on January 27. In the original
trials, both men received more lenient sentences because of their
old age and poor heath. With time already spent in detention, they
ended up having only a few months left to serve in the previous
trial. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980308.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Chairman Ends Visit to Costa Rica </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, March 7 (Xinhua) -- World Bank President James
Wolfensohn ended a two-day visit to Costa Rica Friday.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, he announced a donation of 7 million
U.S. dollars to Costa Rica to protect the species of flora and
fauna present in the Costa Rican tropical forests.
</P>
<P>
He also signed an agreement on the disbursement of 500,000
dollars to the Costa Rican National Biodiversity Institute.
</P>
<P>
The half-million-dollar donation by Japan will assist the
programs of this country to plant 15 million trees every year in
7,000 hectares of natural forests, and to protect other 50,000
hectares of forests in natural regeneration.
</P>
<P>
Wolfensohn said Costa Rica "has demonstrated that the
protection of the environment is not a luxury, but an activity of
life."
</P>
<P>
Approximately 25 percent of the Costa Rican territory have been
classified as national parks, natural forests, and other forms of
reserve since 1970.
</P>
<P>
For this reason, 40 percent of the Costa Rican territory is now
covered with trees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
