<DOCNO> XIE19980308.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Government Committed to Enhance Status of Women: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 8 (Xinhua) -- The Pakistani government is
committed and has the political will to enhance the status of
women in society and ensure their full and effective integration
into the mainstream of society.
</P>
<P>
In Pakistan, women are free to enter into any profession of
their choice both in the public and private sectors, said
President of Pakistan Rafiq Tarar in his message on the occasion
of the International Women's Day being observed on March 8.
</P>
<P>
He said that the role of women in national development would be
further enhanced and consolidated in future, according to the
Associated Press of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan joins the international community to observe the
International Women's Day on March 8, 1998 to focus attention and
reaffirm its commitment towards the protection of women's rights,
the president said.
</P>
<P>
"Protection and promotion of human rights is the cardinal
principle of our faith and constitution," he added.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif has also sent a message
on the occasion in which he said that "today is indeed a historic
day as it marks reiteration of the commitment of all nations for
the cause and development of women."
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan is a modern democratic Islamic state. Our
Constitution has specific provisions to safeguard and advance the
interests of women," he said. "It is also a matter of satisfaction
that our society as a whole holds womenfolk in high esteem."
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, while celebrating the International Women's Day
in Pakistan, "we all must further ensure in our own respective
spheres of activity to end the violation of women's civil,
political, economic, social and cultural rights," Sharif said.
</P>
<P>
"I invite every citizen to join the government towards this
end, " he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
