<DOCNO> XIE19980308.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Restrictions on Renminbi Business to Be Loosened </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 8 (Xinhua) -- China is considering loosening the
restrictions imposed on foreign banks wishing to deal in the local
currency, according to a senior central bank official.
</P>
<P>
"The bank is studying ways to give more channels to foreign
banks to raise renminbi funds," said Di Weiping, vice-president of
the Shanghai branch of the People's Bank of China.
</P>
<P>
Today's China Daily quoted Di as saying that detailed
regulations are in the process of elaboration and will gradually
be released.
</P>
<P>
On the subject of recent financial crisis in Southeast Asia, Di
stressed that China will continue to carry out its opening policy
to gradually liberalize its capital market.
</P>
<P>
According to Di, nine foreign banks have been conducting local
currency business on a trial basis in Shanghai since early 1997,
and the central bank is considering giving approval for a second
group of foreign banks to conduct local currency business.
</P>
<P>
After nearly one year of experience, these banks are moving
forward in accepting renminbi deposits and issuing loans.
</P>
<P>
More than 50 foreign financial institutions have been set up in
Shanghai, including 41 banking subsidiaries, six insurance
companies and five finance companies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
