<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Women Play Greater Role </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 7 (Xinhua) -- Women hold up half the sky. This is
true in Russia where women, which make up 53 percent of the
country's population, are playing a greater role in socio-economic
life, especially in state administrative affairs.
</P>
<P>
Russian women are more educated than men. In colleges and
universities, 55 percent of the registered students are female
while in polytechnic schools, the rate is as high as 59 percent.
</P>
<P>
About half of the employed in Russia are women who maintain a
dominant presence in government departments dealing with health,
sports, social security, culture, education and arts.
</P>
<P>
Compared with its 11 percent presence in the State Duma (the
lower house of Russian parliament), women make up 56 percent of
Russia's public servants, including nine percent of government
officials.
</P>
<P>
However, more Russian women are jobless than men. Of the
unemployed women, 40 percent are below the age of 30 and 47
percent are well-educated.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, every 100 Russian women give birth to only 123
children, which is much lower than the minimum of 215 children
needed to maintain the simple reproduction of the country's
population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
