<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Investors Still Prefer Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 8 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines still managed to
pull in a bigger chunk of foreign capital compared with other
Asian economies last year, an indication of greater investor
confidence in the country's economic climate, the Philippine Star
said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Citing central bank figures, the paper said that net private
capital flows into the Philippines last year accounted for 6.3
percent of gross domestic product (GDP), comparatively higher than
Malaysia's 4.7 percent, Indonesia's 1.6 percent and South Korea's
2.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
In Thailand, there was a net outflow of capital last year,
nearly 11 percent of its GDP, a marked turnaround from a net
inflow of 9.3 percent in 1996, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The net flow of private capital refers to the movement of
direct investments, portfolio investments and other investments
such as those in the short-term to long-term debt market.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that direct investment in the Philippines
reached 1.6 percent of GDP last year, the same level as in 1996.
</P>
<P>
But portfolio investments in the Philippines dropped to a net
outflow of 5.2 percent of GDP last year, the highest in the
region, although no country experienced a net portfolio inflow
greater than 0.4 percent of GDP in 1997, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
