<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Agriculture Highlighted in NPC Discussion (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 8 (Xinhua) -- Agriculture has been a hot topic
among deputies to China's top legislature, the National People's
Congress, in session here since last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
This is despite the fact the country has had good harvests for
the last three years.
</P>
<P>
Deputies expressed appreciation for a decision made by the NPC
to establish a committee on agriculture and rural affairs to step
up agriculture-related legislation and supervision.
</P>
<P>
"For China's agricultural sector, concerns should not be
limited to how to maintain a steady increase in grain production,"
said Lu Xueyi, a deputy from the Chinese Academy of Social
Sciences. "They also cover how to bring about progress in backward
farming practices, income increases for the 800 million rural
residents and improvement in their living standard."
</P>
<P>
These have a bearing on the stability and development of rural
China and even those of the entire nation, he said.
</P>
<P>
China started its economic reform program by adopting a
household-based farming system in rural areas. The move has led to
impressive growth in agricultural production and farmers' incomes.
In his government work report, Premier Li Peng announced that the
government allows and encourages farmers to renew their land
contracts for a term of 30 years.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Wang Maolin, secretary of the Provincial Committee of
the Communist Party of China in Hunan, a major grain producer,
said China is weak in agriculture infrastructure and has an
irrational agricultural structure and a backward farm produce
processing industry. "These problems must be addressed," Wang
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
