<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Menem Addresses Open Letter to Argentine Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, March 7 (Xinhua) -- Argentine President Carlos
Menem addressed Saturday an open letter to the women of the
country, in which he highlights the efforts made by the feminine
sector in its perennial struggle against social inequalities.
</P>
<P>
Menem said in his message on the occasion of Women's
International Day, the road they have traveled in their effort to
preserve and defend the rights of the workers.
</P>
<P>
The Argentine president paid homage to the 129 women who died
March 8, 1908, in the defense of their rights of equality, and to
all those who struggled for reaching that purpose.
</P>
<P>
The president underscored the life of Eva Peron, former
president Juan Domingo Peron wife, considering her "the great
architect of the daily life of women in the last 50 years."
</P>
<P>
Menem said that thanks to Eva Peron, Argentine women voted for
the first time in the political life of Argentina," since at that
time only men had the right to vote.
</P>
<P>
He said the efforts of his government to preserve women's
rights in the economic and political fields, emphasizing "the law
of feminine presence," approved during his mandate.
</P>
<P>
The president said that he feels himself "proud and moved" by
women, "for their everyday work, for their continuous struggle
against inequalities and exclusions, and for the courage they
cover themselves with."
</P>
<P>
Finally, Menem expressed his recognition to all the women for
"all the effort and dedication they apply every day in their
labor, in the building of their families," and "in making of
Argentina a country where to live is dignifying." 
</P>
</TEXT>
