<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peru Loses Big Areas of Cultives Because of El Nino </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, March 7 (Xinhua) -- 29,275 hectares or 2.2 percent of the
total of Peruvian cultivated areas lost because of El Nino
phenomenon since August of 1997, according to Agriculture Ministry
statistics Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The north of the country had the biggest losses with 13,874
hectares affected, which add to the 13,507 hectares of land
affected mainly by floods and intense rain.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture Minister Rodolfo Munante has estimated that the
losses are some 74 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The losses could have been bigger if preventive measures had
not been implemented, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
The El Nino effect on agriculture started to be noticed from
the middle of last year, said Munante.
</P>
<P>
In other aspects, the phenomenon caused the death of 203
persons, according to figures published Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The the number of persons affected by El Nino until February 20
increased to 310,937 in Peru. 
</P>
</TEXT>
