<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Acts to Combat Acid Rain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 8 (Xinhua) -- China has declared war on acid
rain by establishing two special control zones and enforcing
charges on enterprises that discharge sulphur dioxide, the main
pollutant responsible.
</P>
<P>
The control zones, located in southern and central parts f the
country, cover 11.4 percent of the national territory, but they
discharge 60 percent of the sulphur dioxide in China, today's
China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that the establishment of the two zones is in
line with the special requirements of the revised Law on Air
Pollution Prevention and Control passed August 1995.
</P>
<P>
The aim is to curb the deteriorating trend of acid rain and
sulphur dioxide pollution in these areas by 2000. Industrial
pollution sources located there are to achieve state standards in
treating sulphur dioxide before discharge by the turn of the
century.
</P>
<P>
The Paper quoted Xie Zhenhua, director of the National
Environmental Protection Agency, as saying that no new mines for
high-sulphur coal -- whose sulphur content exceeds 3 percent --
will be dug in these two zones.
</P>
<P>
In another move, China is likely to subject more areas to
charges for sulphur dioxide emissions.
</P>
<P>
The practice has been applied experimentally since 1992 in
Guangdong and Guizhou provinces and the cities of Liuzhou,
Nanning, Guilin, Hangzhou, Qingdao, Chongqing, Changsha, Yihang
and Yibin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
