<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Balkan Countries Agree to Coordinate in Combating AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, March 7 (Xinhua) -- Four Balkan countries have agreed to
work for more coordination between institutions in their countries
for timely information on the spread of AIDS (acquired
immuno-deficiency syndrome).
</P>
<P>
At an international conference on AIDS which ended here
Saturday, participants from Albania, Bulgaria, the Republic of
Macedonia and Turkey warned that though their countries are still
considered as countries of low AIDS incidence yet there are
conditions for an increase in the number of HIV (human
immuno-deficiency virus) carriers.
</P>
<P>
The three-day conference, organized within the framework of the
United Nations Program against AIDS, highlighted the priority
areas in working to curb the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
The participants agreed to work out national strategic plans to
combat factors leading to the spread of AIDS and underscored the
need to review national legislation and harmonize it with European
norms protecting people from AIDS.
</P>
<P>
They also expressed alarm over the growth of AIDS incidence
among drug addicts in Moldova, Belarus and Ukraine, warning that a
similar boom is possible in the Balkan region as well. 
</P>
</TEXT>
