<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tianjin Rural Economy in Booming Cycle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, March 8 (Xinhua) -- Tianjin, the largest port city in
north China, has witnessed an overall rural economic growth in
recent years with the 1997 GDP standing at 52.8 billion yuan, up
21.2 percent on 1996.
</P>
<P>
Rural revenues for 1997 stood at 2.77 billion yuan, up 18.6
percent over 1996, with per capita income for rural residents
rising by 12.9 percent to 3,548 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Despite prevailing drought over the past 10 years, Tianjin
reaped yet another good grain harvest of 2.06 billion kg in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The local animal husbandry and aquiculture sectors have also
enjoyed stable growth, with output of fresh meat, eggs and milk
reaching 236,000 tons, 240,000 tons, and 120,000 tons
respectively. A substantial portion of the city's total output for
related products was shipped to provinces and cities throughout
the nation.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin's rural enterprises generated 131.2 billion yuan in
business turnover and 14.1 billion yuan in pre-tax profits in
1997, up 14 percent and 2.6 percent respectively on 1996. Said
businesses exported products valued at 15.5 billion yuan during
1997, up 9.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The city's service sector, including catering, transportation
and tourism, has emerged as a new economic growth factor in rural
areas, with the sector recording a 1997 turnover of 25 billion
yuan, up 25 percent on the previous year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
