<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Operation Allows Man With Three Tongues To Speak Normally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, March 8 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese farmer who was born
with three tongues, can now eat and speak normally after having
received an operation at a military hospital in Chongqing recently.
</P>
<P>
The 32-year-old farmer, Xiang Shihua, from Sichuan province in
southwest China, was born with one tongue, but a second smaller
one appeared when he was five, followed by a third.
</P>
<P>
His largest tongue was 35.5 cm long, 15 cm wide, and 11 cm
thick, while the other two were 9 cm long and of varying widths
and thicknesses.
</P>
<P>
For the past 20 years, Xiang could not speak to others normally
and had to subsist on a liquid diet.
</P>
<P>
Doctors at Chongqing's Southwest Military Hospital said that
Xiang's disease was a kind of fibroma, or benign tumor, and
performed an operation to remove the two extra tongues for him
last month. Medical authorities say they've found no record of a
similar case, and that Xiang's family had no history of related
diseases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
