<DOCNO> XIE19980308.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CPPCC Members Response Positively to Institutional Restructuring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 8 (Xinhua) -- Members of China's leading
advisory body said it is imperative to press on with the
government structural reform so as to establish an efficient,
coordinated and standardized administrative system.
</P>
<P>
Over the past days, members of the Ninth National Committee of
the Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC)
have discussed the Plan Concerning Institutional Restructuring of
the State Council delivered by State Councillor Luo Gan Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The overstaffing of governmental institutions will surely
result in low efficiency, whereas institutional restructuring can
reduce the size of staff and raise efficiency," said Li Hanqiu, a
CPPCC Ninth National Committee member with the China Peasants and
Workers Democratic Party (CPWDP) Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
The change of government functions is the major target of
institutional restructuring this time. Many specialists with the
CPPCC said that the restructuring should readjust four types of
relations: namely those between government and market, government
and enterprises, government and society, and central government
and local government.
</P>
<P>
Dong Fureng, a noted economist, said that in the past planned
economy, the government took charge of the allocation of resources
and had to handly all things, big or small. Therefore, the
government is huge and unwiedly with a concentration of power.
</P>
<P>
"In the shift from the planned economy to market economy, it is
easy to trade much government power for money," the economist
said. "To eradicate corruption in the government, institutional
restructuring can be taken as a fundamental way out."
</P>
<P>
In today's market economy, the government should play the role
of stabilizing the market, safeguarding market rules and ensuring
justice in the market, instead of making decisions for the market,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Many CPPCC members held that there will surely be difficulties
in downsizing government the institutions and cutting staff. But as long
as there is a will, there will be a way and the prospect is bright.
</P>
<P>
Liang Xiongjian, who works with the China Institute of
Telecommunications, noted that in the process of institutional
restructuring, the state-owned assets of the existing ministries
and commissions must be supersized and managed well. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980308.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fujian Rural Enterprises Experience Robust Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, March 8 (Xinhua) -- Rural and township enterprises in
east China's Fujian province witnessed robust growth during 1997,
with their total export volume ranking fourth when compared to
counterparts across the nation.
</P>
<P>
Fujian's 730,000 rural and township enterprises in operation at
the end of 1997 had a total output value of 358.2 billion yuan, up
22 percent on the previous year, according to official statistics.
</P>
<P>
In addition, their total industrial output value jumped by 21
percent to 233 billion yuan, with the value of export goods rising
by 16 percent to 63.5 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Fujian is home to China's most developed rural and township
enterprise sector, with over 8,900 export enterprises currently
marketing products in over 60 countries and regions. Fujian has
also approved some 3,600 township enterprises involving foreign
funds
</P>
<P>
Fujian has extended great efforts to create large rural and
township enterprise groups capable of achieving economic
operations of scale. The province is home to 52 large provincial-
and 14 national-level rural and township enterprise groups.
</P>
</TEXT>
