<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heavy Industrial Base Attracts More Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 8 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China's Liaoning
province, one of the country's major heavy industrial bases, has
emerged as one of the hot spots of foreign investment in China.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning ranks third among all Chinese provinces in terms of
foreign investment volume, following closely behind Jiangsu and
Guangdong provinces.
</P>
<P>
The province attracted 5.5 billion US dollars in contracted
foreign investment during 1997, up 9.6 percent on the previous
year, according to local officials.
</P>
<P>
The 3.06 billion US dollars actually used during the year was
up 29 percent on 1996. Foreign funds accounted for 26 percent of
the province's total fixed assets investments in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The 16,473 foreign-funded firms approved by the end of 1997
involved 25.6 billion US dollars of foreign funds.
</P>
<P>
Experts note that the province's strong heavy industrial base,
which is currently undergoing extensive renovations and upgrading,
provides foreign investors with a golden opportunity for
investment.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the province attracted 680 million US dollars for 72
foreign-funded projects, with a substantial portion of related
funds earmarked for technological upgrading of state-owned
industrial enterprises.  
</P>
</TEXT>
