<HEADLINE> Spark Program Benefits Sichuan Farmers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, March 8 (Xinhua) -- Some 55,000 farmers in southwest
China's Sichuan Province escaped poverty during 1997 and this can
be attributed to the implementation of the Spark Program.
</P>
<P>
Sichuan, a traditionally agricultural province, invested over
two billion yuan in 645 Spark Program projects during 1997, with
said projects yielding a total output value of 4.22 billion yuan
and pretax profits of 700 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government introduced the Spark Program in the
1980s as part of an effort to introduce farmers to advanced
technology needed to promote the rural economy.
</P>
<P>
The province focused efforts on profit-making agricultural
operations, including the production of vegetables, fruits,
traditional Chinese herbs, livestock and aquatics. The extensive
effort yielded a total output value of 900 million yuan and pretax
profits of 70 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Sichuan has also attempted to train farmers by sponsoring
diverse training classes which encourage the full use of science
and technology. 
</P>
</TEXT>
