<HEADLINE> German Greens Party Sticks to Demand to Raise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 7 (Xinhua) -- Germany's opposition Greens party
today decided to hold on to its controversial demand for a radical
increase in the country's gasoline price despite warnings that it
would undermine the party's bid to come to power in Bonn after the
September general elections.
</P>
<P>
After a heated debate at a party congress in the eastern German
city of Magdeburg, the ecologically-minded Greens voted to
campaign for a ten-year gradual increase of the gasoline price to
about five marks (2.7 U.S. dollars) per liter from the current
level of about 1.65 marks (0.90 dollars).
</P>
<P>
The fund raised would be used to finance big cuts in the
country's huge labour costs, the party said.
</P>
<P>
The Greens is seeking to form a coalition with the largest
opposition Social Democratic Party (SPD) to replace Chancellor
Helmut Kohl's center-right ruling coalition at the general
elections on September 27 this year.
</P>
<P>
Analysts, however, say that the two parties still have much to
do to reconcile their policies in order to form a viable alliance.
</P>
<P>
Indeed, the SPD today did not hesitate to distance itself from
the Greens demand for the gasoline price hike.
</P>
<P>
"It is nonsense and we will not do that," SPD chancellor
candidate Gerhard Schroeder was quoted by the German press as
saying.
</P>
<P>
SPD party chairman Oskar Lafontaine also indicated that his
party would pursue a more realistic eco-policy.
</P>
<P>
Separately, Schroeder today also set a goal for the SPD to win
40 percent of the vote at the general elections in order to become
the largest single party in the federal parliament.
</P>
<P>
At Germany's 1994 general elections, the SPD came in at 36.4
percent and the Greens 7.3 percent, compared with 48.4 percent won
by Kohl's ruling coalition consisting of Christian Democratic
Union (CDU), Christian Social Union (CSU) and the junior partner
Free Democratic Party (FDP). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
