<HEADLINE> Jordanian King in Measured Tone Over Iraq-US Dialog </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, February 7 (Xinhua) -- King Hussein of Jordan has
appeared low-key in talking his proposal to hold direct dialog
between the United States and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters upon his return from a Gulf trip
Saturday, Hussein said that he was not entrusted by any party to
make such a proposal to Washington.
</P>
<P>
"I just said what I believe is right and what might sometimes
come, of course, after strict and full implementation of the
existing agreements to remove completely the Iraqi people's
suffering," the king said.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that the United Arab Emirates (UAE) and Oman
shared the stand with Jordan on regional issues, including the
opening of direct dialogs between Iraq and the U.S..
</P>
<P>
Hussein began his five-day visit to the UAE and Oman last
Tuesday to sell the idea.
</P>
<P>
The U.S., however, said on Wednesday that it had "no plans and
no interest" in opening a direct dialog with the Iraqi leadership.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Jordanian Prime Minister Abdul Salam Majali, who
accompanied Hussein in his Gulf trip and returned here, said the
king has not officially presented the idea to the U.S.
Administration.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that Hussein would make such a proposal to U.S.
President Bill Clinton during their meeting in Washington
scheduled for next Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"When he meets President Clinton and puts forward such ideas,
we will see whether there will be an American response or not,"
said Majali.
</P>
<P>
Referring to how Arab nations have responded to the proposal,
Majali said that "everyone is with this dialog."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has been accusing Iraq of not complying with the
United Nations resolutions and hiding weapons of mass destruction,
and Iraq denounces U.S. manipulation of arms inspections in an
attempt to prolong international sanctions on it.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's refusal to grant free access to the U.N. Special
Commission charged with eliminating its banned weapons brought the
country to the brink of a military attack by the U.S. last month,
which was averted by U.N. chief Kofi Annan's success in mediating
a peaceful settlement.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. commission must certify that Iraq has destroyed all
its weapons of mass destruction before the U.N. Security Council
lifts the crippling economic sanctions imposed on Iraq in 1990
after its invasion of Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
